<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Calls for Extraordinary Duma Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
Friday signed a message to the State Duma, the lower house of
parliament, suggesting that an extraordinary meeting should be
held to discuss a package of stabilization draft laws.
</P>
<P>
According to presidential press secretary Sergei Yastrzhembsky,
the president put the suggestion when making a working visit to
Novgorod.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's proposal will be discussed by a meeting of the Duma
Council which will be held on August 17.
</P>
<P>
Russian Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko said Thursday that if
an extraordinary meeting of the Duma Council were held after
August 20 and the stabilization draft laws endorsed by the Duma
deputies, the laws could go into effect from September 1 after
being ratified by the Federation Council.
</P>
<P>
Duma budget committee deputy chairman Gennady Kulik Friday
expressed support for the president's appeal for an emergency
meeting of the Duma, saying that the appeal "proceeded from the
real situation and the effort to fulfill obligations taken by
the government in connection with credits of international fiscal
organizations."
</P>
<P>
Earlier Friday, Yeltsin said that "at present there is no need
to convene an extra session of the Duma," but he did not rule out
the possibility to use his constitutional right to call the
session.
</P>
<P>
Under the Duma regulations, decisions on holding extraordinary
sessions should be taken on the basis of a written suggestion
coming either from the president or from the Duma chairman, or on
the suggestion of one fifth of the total number of MPs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
