<HEADLINE> Simitis Says Greece Adheres to Peace Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Greece pursued a policy of peace
and adhered to respect of international law and international
treaties, Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a message on the eve of Greece's armed forces day, which
will be marked Saturday, Simitis said that Greece, as a member of
the European Union (EU) and as a country with full understanding
of the critical nature of the times and the climate of fluidity
and uncertainty plaguing the wider region of the eastern
Mediterranean, was exercising a policy of peace, based on a
credible deterrent force, in addition to its unwavering
persistence to respect of international law and adherence of the
international treaties.
</P>
<P>
He described the Greek armed forces as "the cornerstone of a
strong Greece" and "a true bridge of understanding between East
and West."
</P>
<P>
Greece's sensitive geographical position demanded the
materialization of a defense police founded exclusively on the
right of self-defense, which is consolidated in the U.N. charter,
the premier said.
</P>
<P>
Simitis stressed that a strong Greece was an economically and
militarily shielded Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
