<HEADLINE> Irish PM Thanks U.S. Support for N.Irish Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Ireland's Prime Minister Bertie
Ahern Friday thanked the American leaders for their support to
the Northern Irish peace process.
</P>
<P>
"One of the most satisfying aspects of the search for peace in
Northern Ireland has been the huge support and encouragement we
have got from our friends abroad, but none more so than from those
in America," Ahern was quoted as saying in a statement.
</P>
<P>
At a luncheon with Newt Gingrich, speaker of the U.S. House of
Representatives, Ahern also had a personal note of thanks to
Gingrich, who is in the Republic of Ireland with a congressional
delegation for an eight-day visit to Ireland and Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The conflicting political parties in Northern Ireland reached a
historic peace agreement in April, which is aimed at ending the
30-year-old bloody violence in Britain's divided province.
</P>
<P>
"You too, Mr Speaker, can take credit for the outcome -- all
the participants returned to Ireland from your lunch, galvanized
to `do the deal,'" Ahern said.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed his gratitude to U.S. President Bill Clinton
for his support and said he was looking forward to Clinton's visit
to Northern Ireland and the republic on September 3. 
</P>
</TEXT>
