<HEADLINE> Cyprus Stresses Importance of Joint Defense Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Defense Minister
Yiannakis Omirou Friday underlined the importance of the joint
defense pact with Greece to the security of the Mediterranean
island.
</P>
<P>
In a message to his Greek counterpart Akis Tsohatzopoulos on
the occasion of Greek Armed Forces Day on Saturday, Omirou said "I
would like to express my sincere thanks for the (Greek) nation's
firm solidarity, led by the Armed Forces, to the struggle of the
people of Cyprus to end the Turkish occupation and restore the
independence, sovereignty and territorial integrity of the
Republic."
</P>
<P>
The joint defense pact, signed in November 1993 by the two
governments, provides that Greece will offer Cyprus air, land and
sea support in case of a new Turkish offensive against the island.
</P>
<P>
Omirou described the defense pact as "a practical expression of
Hellenism's solidarity toward Cyprus at these crucial hours,"
adding that "it has strengthened the feeling of security among our
people."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the pact, along with Cyprus' bid to join the
European Union (EU), are the two main pillars of the policy shared
by the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since Turkish troops
landed and seized the northern third of the island in 1974 in the
aftermath of a failed pro-Athens coup by Greek Cypriots in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Turkey continues to maintain a 35,000-strong military presence
in the island's northern third, despite U.N. resolutions calling
for their withdrawal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
