<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Calls for Peaceful Solution to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS Ababa, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia Friday called upon
the Organization of African Unity (OAU) and all concerned to
find a peaceful resolution to the over three-month Ethio-Eritrean
crisis.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here, the Ethiopian Foreign Ministry
said that the OAU ministerial committee dealing with the
crisis has affirmed that the Badme Area was under Ethiopian
administration prior to the period between May 6 and 12, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The statement said, ''In the face of incontrovertible
evidence, the OAU committee conclusively affirmed that Badme Area
has been administered by Ethiopia''.
</P>
<P>
The OAU committee also stated that "what happened in Badme
between May 6-12 constitutes a fundamental element of the crisis"
and that the challenge is "to find a soluiton to that problem
within the framework of a comprehensive settlement of the
conflict in all its dimensions,'' said the statement.
</P>
<P>
It continued to provide evidences that the Badme was
administered by Ethiopia, noting that a census was carried out by
Ethiopia in 1994 registering 6,425 residents in the town and the
surrounding localities, no less than six Ethiopia elections were
held in Badme between June 1992 and February 1996, and the Badme
Area elected a member to sit in the Ehtiopian parliament.
</P>
<P>
The OAU ministerial committee met in Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso
on August 1-2, 1998 and considered the report of the committee of
amabassaodrs which visited Eritrea and Ethiopia from June 30 to
July 9. The ministerial committe has submited its recommendations
to the heads of state of the OAU high level delegation for their
consideration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
