<HEADLINE> France Denies Involvement in D.R. Congo Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 14 (Xinhua) -- France Friday once against denied
any involvement in the on-going war in the Democratic Republic of
the Congo (DRC) after a DRC rebel source claimed that it had the
"implicit" support of both France and the United States.
</P>
<P>
"France has nothing to mess with in the current events in the
Democratic Republic of the Congo," said the French Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
A DRC source in Brussels was quoted by local media reports as
saying that six months after the fall of President Mobutu and
after President Laurent Kabila was found to be "not the man of
situation," the rebels contacted Paris and Washington for action
to "normalize the situation."
</P>
<P>
"The United States and France have given their implicit
agreement," said the unidentified source.
</P>
<P>
An earlier report by the French weekly satirical publication
Canard Enchaine quoted an official source as saying that the
rebellion had the "blessing" of President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
French Delegate Minister in charge of cooperation with Africa
Charles Josselin said earlier this week that Kabila was not
"inevitably made for his role" (as president of the DRC). 
</P>
