<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Commission Denies Accepting External Direction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Special
Commission for disarmament in Iraq Friday rejected media reports
that it has been given and accepted "external direction" in its
operational activities.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued through the U.N. spokesman's office,
the commission, or UNSCOM, said that "these allegations are
false."
</P>
<P>
It noted that members of the U.N. Security Council acknowledge
the "key distinction" between policy decisions and operational
decisions regarding the UNSCOM and they respect the distinction.
</P>
<P>
"All policy decisions on the UNSCOM activities are taken by the
Security Council but operational decisions are taken by the
executive chairman," said the UNSCOM whose executive chairman is
Australian Richard Butler.
</P>
<P>
"Consultations on policy matters take place regularly between
the executive chairman and council members but all operational
decisions are taken by the executive chairman who has not been
given and would find it invidious were any attempt made to direct
his operational decisions or to micro-manage the day-to-day work
of the Special Commission," it stated.
</P>
<P>
The press release was issued in the wake of a Washington Post
report which said U.S. officials have asked Butler to try delaying
surprise arms inspections to avoid confrontation with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
A deadlock in arms inspections between Iraq and the UNSCOM has
emerged since Iraq decided Wednesday last week to suspend
cooperation with the UNSCOM, requesting that the UNSCOM be
restructured and moved from New York to Geneva or Vienna to reduce
what it calls U.S. influence.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic efforts are being made for the resumption of
inspections following U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's
suggestions to the Security Council that Iraq be engaged more
closely in finding ways to resolve the Iraq-UNSCOM differences.
</P>
