<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Endorses Draft Policy on HIV-AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Council of Ministers of
Ethiopia Friday unanimously endorsed the draft policy on HIV-AIDS
and decided to put the policy into force.
</P>
<P>
The national HIV-AIDS policy is aimed at launching integrated
prevention activities by governmental, non-governmental and other
pertinent bodies, making some amendments to the draft policy, the
Ethiopian News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Council of Ministers said that the number of Ethiopians
contracting the deadly disease is on the rise, making the country
one of the countries where AIDS is expanding at an alarming rate.
</P>
<P>
Although many preventive measures have been taken, so far they
have not been streamlined under a national policy, the council
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
It said that the need to direct efforts on the prevention of
HIV-AIDS necessitated the policy which is designed as part of the
national health strategy.
</P>
<P>
According to the national HIV-AIDS control program of
Ethiopia, the HIV-AIDS epidemic has increasingly spread among
Ethiopians in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Only one person out of every 100 Ethiopians was HIV-infected
in 1989; in 1993, three persons out of every 100 were infected by
HIV virus and in 1996, out of every 100 Ethiopians, five were
infected by the deadly disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
