<HEADLINE> Romanian Prime Minister on Foreign Debt, Credit Rating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, August 14 (Xinhua) -- It is not logical for the
Moody's rating agency to announce it will diminish Romania's
credit rating, Romanian Prime Minister Radu Vasile told the local
daily Cronica Romana Friday.
</P>
<P>
"I think it is not normal to use political disagreements to
consider the credit rating higher," the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said that there are a lot of countries in the world "where
there are deeper and longer political tensions by way of
comparison with Romania."
</P>
<P>
"I would have understood Moody's gesture if our structural
reform had been delayed. But, since such an explanation cannot be
given anymore, they reached the `political environment' issues,"
the prime minister said, adding that these political environment
issues can be found in any democratic country, anytime.
</P>
<P>
Romania's current appraisal, Radu Vasile said, "is not
appropriate and it is connected to certain influence factors." As
a support for his statement, he said, speculations about the
foreign debt of Romania occurred.
</P>
<P>
"It should be clear that we have the smallest foreign debt,
about 8 billion U.S. dollars by way of comparison with Hungary,
the Czech Republic and Poland, while Hungary is one of the heavily
indebted countries in the world," Radu Vasile said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the international financial rating agency
Moody's announced Monday a possible lowering of Romania's credit
rating after its announcement on July 16 of its decision to change
Romania's status from stable to negative.
</P>
<P>
Local economic analyzers consider that Moody's decision is
caused by political instability and not the economic situation.
</P>
<P>
"It is an extremely serious warning because if Romania is
demoted with one more class in the rating hierarchy, it means it
will be completely out of the possible investments list," warned
Ilie Serbanescu, the former minister of reform. 
</P>
</TEXT>
