decisive action to restore stability and confidence in Russia's
economy.
</P>
<P>
During a 40-minute telephone discussion, Clinton and Yeltsin
focused on the economic problems facing Russia, a U.S. official
told reporters on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
It was Clinton's view that the onus was on the shoulders of the
Russian government to take further action on its economy, rather
than on the West to provide more cash, said the official.
</P>
<P>
"The president encouraged President Yeltsin to take some
decisive steps in the next few days that would help change the
market psychology, so to speak, in restoring confidence," he
added.
</P>
<P>
When asked if the two leaders had discussed further
international aid to Russia, the U.S. official replied: "They
didn't talk about specifics. From the president's standpoint, it
is more a case of encouraging the Russian government to take
action."
</P>
<P>
"The president encouraged President Yeltsin to work with his
economic team and take some action sooner rather than later," said
the U.S. official.
</P>
<P>
"They need to keep doing the things that they need to do under
the IMF program. That will both send the right signal to the
markets and improve the climate when the IMF evaluates release of
the next tranche," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and Yeltsin will meet in Moscow early in September with
economic issues likely to dominate the summit. 
