<HEADLINE> Pentagon to Give All Troops Anthrax Shots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Defense Department of the
United States will begin to inoculate all U.S. troops against the
deadly threat of anthrax next week, the Pentagon announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
Troops in the Persian Gulf began receiving the vaccinations
earlier this year. The next round of vaccinations will be the
troops serving in Southeast Asia and South Korea, and all of the
2.4 million active and reserve forces will be inoculated by about
2004, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
"This is an efficient, effective and safe way to protect our
forces against an emerging threat," Defense Secretary William
Cohen said while announcing the start of the program.
</P>
<P>
So far, 48,000 troops have received the inoculations, said Dr.
Sue Bailey, assistant secretary of defense for health affairs.
</P>
<P>
Michael Cowan, deputy director for medical readiness for the
Joint Chiefs of Staff, said there was an increasing threat of
chemical and biological attacks from several nations that are
thought to be developing such weapons.
</P>
<P>
The immunization program consists of a series of six shots for
each service member over an 18-month period, followed by an annual
booster.  
</P>
</TEXT>
