<HEADLINE> U.S. Admits Discussing Timing of U.N. Inspections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The White House said on
Friday that Washington had discussed with U.N. weapons
inspectors on what time would be best for the weapons
inspection teams to stage surprise inspections in Iraq, but
denied giving any order to change their plans.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post said that the Clinton administration had
intervened secretly for months, to dissuade U.N. weapons
inspection teams from mounting surprise inspections in Iraq
because it wished to avoid a new crisis with Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
But White House spokesman Mike McCurry said: "We have been
talking with them "about the best way to perform their mission --
timing, outcome, best way to achieve their mission -- but we don't
order them not to conduct their mission."
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post said on August 4, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright urged chief U.N. weapons inspector Richard
Butler to rescind closely held orders for a inspection team to
mount "challenge inspections" at some sites where intelligence
reports suggested there might be banned weapons components.
</P>
<P>
A State Department official said that the date of
conversation reported by the Post was correct "but not the
substance or the tone."
</P>
<P>
Albright herself admitted that she had consulted with Butler on
the latest standoff between the Iraqis and the weapons inspection
teams, but denied she had given him any instructions.
</P>
<P>
"I do not tell Chairman Butler what to do," she told reporters.
</P>
<P>
She said it was up to Butler "where, when and how" he makes
his inspections.
</P>
<P>
Asked if she had told Butler, as the Washington Post
reported, that now was not a good time to make surprise
inspections, Albright said: "As I said we've had conversations.
I do not want to go into those conversations. I do not tell
Chairman Butler what to do.  
</P>
