to join their colleagues, South African Press Association (SAPA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
The committee was set up earlier this week in terms of an
agreement brokered by South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki
to defuse the political crisis in the mountainous kingdom.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has sent four representatives including
Constitutional Court Deputy President Pius Langa and Mbeki's
legal adviser Mojunku Gumbi, while Botswana has further provided
three members.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe has apparently not finalized its representation yet.
</P>
<P>
The panel was immediately briefed by the South African mission
in Lesotho's capital Maseru.
</P>
<P>
It will work with, among others, Lesotho's Independent
Electoral Commission and opposition parties and has been asked to
report back within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Lesotho government and opposition parties have agreed to
abide by the committee's findings. Lesotho Prime Minister
Pakalitha Mosisili even pledged that he would step down if the
May 23 general election was proved seriously flawed.
</P>
<P>
Mosisili's Lesotho Congress for Democracy (LCD) won 79 of 80
seats in the National Assembly in the election, but opposition
parties claim that the results were rigged in favor of the LCD.
</P>
<P>
Unrest began last Tuesday when opposition supporters camped
outside the royal palace in Maseru to protest.
</P>
<P>
Clashes between rival factions resulted in nine injuries
Thursday. 
</P>
