<HEADLINE> UK Crackdowns on Police Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A national crackdown on police
corruption has been launched by Britain's Home Department as fresh
evidence suggested that there are far more crooked officers than
had been suspected, according to local media reports.
</P>
<P>
Officers will have to abide by a new code of ethics, which is
expected to ban minor "perks" - such as the use of a police
identity card to gain free admission to clubs - and even stipulate
whether senior officers should be allowed to drink during business
lunches.
</P>
<P>
The code, which will apply to all 120,000 police officers, is
likely to be draconian because of the belief that serious
corruption flows from petty dishonesty.
</P>
<P>
The new rules will be decided when an extensive assessment of
police corruption throughout Britain has been completed, according
to the Times newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The Home Office has called for secret reports from all 43 chief
constables in England and Wales after initial investigations
showed that sleaze was a problem in rural as well as city forces,
with officers recycling seized drugs and using informers to cream
off rewards, the newspaper said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
One Home Office source was quoted as saying: "There is
corruption in every type of force. Not every force has a problem
but no type of force is immune."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
