<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Civil
Affairs today allocated donated funds totaling 90 million yuan
(about 1.09 million U.S. dollars) to the flood-stricken provinces
of Jiangxi, Hunan, Hubei, Jilin and Heilongjiang and the Inner
Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
It also sent disaster relief materials worth 700,000 yuan to
Jiangsu Province in east China.
</P>
<P>
Along with the donation allocation, the ministry issued an
urgent circular requiring concerned local departments to
diligently handle the disaster relief donations.
</P>
<P>
The circular pointed out that the donations can be used only
for relieving the living difficulties of the flood victims,
especially for the restoration and reconstruction of their damaged
houses.
</P>
<P>
Seriously hit disaster areas and their victims must be given
priority in allocating donated materials and funds, the circular
noted.
</P>
<P>
In addition, it emphasized that donations must be allocated in
an adequate and timely fashion to flood victims in accordance with
the donators' will, and no other use can be made of the donations.
</P>
<P>
The Dalian city government donated 4 million yuan as well as
coats and quilts worth 2 million yuan to flooding areas this
morning.
</P>
<P>
Beginning yesterday evening, the Ministry of Civil Affairs
received medicines worth 370,000 yuan and drinking water and water
purification equipment worth one million yuan from Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The State Flood Control and Drought Relief Headquarters sent
4,000 life jackets, the third batch of relief materials, to the
flood-fighting front line in east Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region, north China.
</P>
<P>
So far, the department has provided 14,990 life jackets, 55
motor-driven rubber boats, 30 speed boats, 160 tons of plastic
sheetings, 6.04 million sandbags, and 67,800 square meters of
cloth, as well as special funds totaling 63.5 million yuan, for
flood-stricken areas in Inner Mongolia.  
