<HEADLINE> Nepal's Ruling, Opposition Parties Decide to Join Hands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Nepali Congress
(NC) and the opposition Communist Party of Nepal
(Marxism-Leninism, CPN-ML) have decided to join hands in forming a
coalition government.
</P>
<P>
The NC's Central Working Committee decided Saturday to include
the CPN-ML into the present government led by its president Girija
Prasad Koirala, the party said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The Central Committee of the CPN-ML has decided as well to
align itself with the NC.
</P>
<P>
In April, the NC and the CPN-ML tried to form a coalition
government, but failed due to dispute over the allocation of key
portfolios. Then the NC, the single largest party in parliament
after the CPN-ML broke away from the Communist Party of Nepal
(United Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML) in March, formed a minority
government of its own.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the general elections, which Prime
Minister Girija Prasad Koirala said is scheduled for April/May
1999, lead to the eventual alliance between the two parties.
</P>
<P>
The alliance means a comfortable majority of 128 seats in the
205-seat Lower House of Parliament for the new coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
It is widely expected that the new coalition government will
come into being by Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
