<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Geneticists Warned of Potential Abuse of Genetic Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The International Genetics
Federation (IGF) has urged geneticists all over the world to
prevent their expertise from becoming potential weapons against
human beings.
</P>
<P>
"Any new knowledge can be used as potential weapons against
people," said Anthony Griffiths, the IGF's Secretary General.
</P>
<P>
"To avoid the abuse of this knowledge, you must ensure that it
is used to complement the goal that is mentioned as the theme of
this congress 'Better Life for All,'" the Canadian geneticist told
today's closing ceremony of the 18th International Congress of
Genetics.
</P>
<P>
His remarks concluded heated discussions of the controversial
relationship between fast-developing genetic technology and
ethics, legislation, and other social issues during the six-day
congress.
</P>
<P>
Consideration of such issues are important because genetics may
change every aspect of life in the next century, said Qiu Renzong,
a Chinese bio-ethics specialist and a delegate to the academic
event.
</P>
<P>
The congress was described as "successful and fruitful" by the
organizers.
</P>
<P>
"About 2,000 experts from 54 countries and regions attended
more than 70 symposiums and discussions, exchanging ideas on the
latest research in genetics-related fields such as agriculture,
medical treatment, pharmaceutics, longevity and environmental
protection," said Chen Shouyi, secretary general of the congress.
</P>
<P>
Hot topics include achievements in human genome research,
breeding of high-yielding hybrid rice, gene therapy and transgenic
technology.
</P>
<P>
Professor Zhao Shouyuan, a Chinese geneticist at Fudan
University, has been elected as the new president of the IGF,
it was announced at the closing ceremony this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The next congress will be held in the year 2003 in Melbourne,
Australia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
