<HEADLINE> Russian Soyuz TM-28 Docks Manually With MIR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The crew of the Russian Soyuz
TM-28 spaceship succeeded in manually docking with the Mir station
in outer space, the Interfax News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It quoted the Russian Space Center as saying that the automatic
docking control system failed when the spacecraft was 17 meters
from the station.
</P>
<P>
Crew commander Gennady Padalka took over the controls, withdrew
the spaceship to 43 meters from the station and brought it into
contact with the station at a rate of 0.25 meters a second, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The Soyuz TM-28 spaceship was launched from Baikonur on
Thursday with three astronauts -- commander Gennady Padalka,
Sergei Avdeyev and ex-secretary of the Defense Council and
presidential aide, Yuri Baturin, on board.
</P>
<P>
The crew will enter the Mir's basic unit to meet with
occupants, Talgat Musabayev and Nikolai Budarin, there later.
