<HEADLINE> Li Peng Inspects Flooded Areas in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Li Peng, chairman of the
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress, has called
for concerted and continuous efforts to fight the raging floods of
the Nengjiang River in northeast China's Heilongjiang Province
until final victory is achieved.
</P>
<P>
"The flooding situation still remains very serious. Full
preparations should be made to cope with problems and difficulties
that may possibly appear," stressed Li, who is also a member of
the Standing Committee of the Political Bureau of the CPC Central
Committee, while on an inspection to the flood-fighting front line
in Heilongjiang on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Li extended warm regards and paid high tribute to the civilians
and soldiers who are fighting the floods.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that top priority should be given to the
protection of people's lives, and urged that every effort be made
to ensure that the people will be provided with adequate food,
clothing, shelter, and access to medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
From north to south, China is undergoing a major flood
season. The water level of the Nengjiang River is still rising
slightly, and more rain is expected to hit the river, he said.
</P>
<P>
So far this summer, the Nengjiang River has seen four floods,
the largest in history, causing huge losses, affecting millions of
residents, disrupting many sections of the Binzhou railway, and
threatening the safety of the cities of Qiqihar and Daqing.
</P>
<P>
Li said that an initial victory has already been achieved. By
August 13, no breaches had occurred on major levees; no large
reservoirs had been disrupted; and no casualties had been reported
among the tens of thousands of people who were evacuated.
</P>
<P>
Li praised the role that soldiers are playing in the
flood-fighting struggle.
</P>
<P>
While inspecting the Songhua River, Li said that the water
level of Harbin will very probably exceed the record high of 120.3
meters in 1957, and the city should keep on high alert and prepare
for the worst.
</P>
<P>
After the flooding ends, a large reservoir will be built on the
upper reaches of the Nengjiang River to accumulate water, Li said.
</P>
<P>
The Nengjiang River embankments should be consolidated;
barriers to flood prevention should be removed; and the safety of
railways, highways, power facilities, and posts and
telecommunications facilities should be ensured, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
