<HEADLINE> First Group of Iranian Pilgrims Cross into Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 15 (Xinhua) -- For the first time in 18 years,
760 Iranian pilgrims crossed the border into Iraq Saturday to
visit the holy sites of the Shiite Muslims in southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The group was officially seen off at the Khosrawi border point
in Kermanshah province by Iranian Minister of Culture and Islamic
Guidance Ataollah Mohajerani.
</P>
<P>
During their stay in Iraq, the pilgrims will visit holy sites
in Karbala, Najaf and Kazemyn in the south.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony, Mohajerani expressed hope that the
visit would consolidate bonds between the Iranian and Iraqi
nations.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Minister of Endowments and Religious Affairs Abdal-Munim
Ahmad Salih told the Iranian delegation that his country has
restored the holy sites over recent years.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement reached between Iran and Iraq, 3,000
Iranian and Iraqi pilgrims are to travel to either country to pay
pilgrimage to holy sites.
</P>
<P>
Before the eruption of the Iran-Iraq war in 1980, hundreds of
thousands of Iranian pilgrims visited the holy sites for Shiite
Muslims in Iraq every year.
</P>
<P>
In choosing its inaugural group of pilgrims, Iran has given
preference to relatives of the Iranians killed during the 1980-88
Iran-Iraq war.
</P>
<P>
Most of the pilgrims are parents of the men killed in the war.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the 10th anniversary of the end of the war, both
Tehran and Baghdad are speeding up their efforts to solve problems
left from the war so to normalize their ties. 
</P>
