<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Genetics Offers New Evidence of International Mixing On Silk Road </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Genetic studies of a hereditary
disease offers new evidence of integration between nationalities
of Asia and Europe over 2,000 years ago on the Silk Road,
according to Chinese scientists.
</P>
<P>
Researchers at a hospital in Urumqi, capital of northwest
China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, found 12 types of mutant
genes relating to Beta-Thalassemia, a hereditary anemia disease
in Xinjiang, Gansu and Shaanxi provinces in northwest China, the hub
of the ancient Silk Road.
</P>
<P>
Two out of the 12 mutant genes, which are quite common in
India, Pakistan, Iran and the United Arab Emirates, have been
found among the Uygur people in the Kashi region of Xinjiang for
the first time, according to the researchers' report published in
the latest issue of the Chinese Journal of Medical Genetics.
</P>
<P>
Kashi was a major center along the Silk Road to western Asia,
Tibet and India. Scientists say this hereditary disease is the
result of migration and marriage among the various ancient
nationalities.
</P>
<P>
Another type of gene associated with the disease has been found
in many Chinese all over the world. But the incidence diminishes
away from the Silk Road region to the rest of China, Taiwan,
Singapore, Malaysia and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Scientists infer from this that the mutant gene originated in
Gansu and then was spread to Southeast Asia by the migration of
Chinese. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980815.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Xie to Challenge Polgar for Chess Crown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, Northeast China, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Xie
Jun won the right to challenge women's reigning world chess
champion Zsuzsa Polgar of Hungary as Russian Alisa Galliamova
pulled out of the FIDE Women's Candidates Final Match here on
Saturday afternoon for an unexplained reason.
</P>
<P>
Xie was declared winner one hour into the make-believe game.
There was no explanation from Galliamova's camp for her no-show.
</P>
<P>
"I really hope that Galliamova would have made it in the last
minute," Xie said. "I'm sorry that she didn't appear."
</P>
<P>
"Anyway, I deserve the right to challenge Polgar," the former
world champion added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
