<HEADLINE> Worst Flood Expected To Hit Harbin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Sometime around August 21,
Harbin, capital of northeast China's Heilongjiang Province, is
expected to face its worst flooding since 1949, local
water-control experts warned today.
</P>
<P>
They forecast that in about one week, water levels on the
Songhua River passing the city will rise to a record high of 120.3
meters, 2.2 meters above the danger line.
</P>
<P>
A flood peak is now roaring down the river at 3:00 pm today,
the water level on the river at Harbin rose as high as 119.36
meters, 1.25 meters above the danger level, with a water flow of
9,540 cubic meters per second, according to the State Flood
Control and Drought Relief Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Harbin imposed a curfew at several sections of the Songhua
River embankments yesterday. About 500,000 local people and
soldiers have been busy working along the river embankments
and residents living in possible danger areas have been
evacuated to safe places.  
</P>
</TEXT>
