<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: A Trip Through War-torn Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRISTINA, Yugoslavia, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Our car was
zigzagging up the crater-dotted road in the mountains of western
Kosovo, a Yugoslav province, when two men in Serbian police
uniforms emerged from behind the bushes and blocked our path.
</P>
<P>
They pulled back bolts of their submachine guns, obviously
because of the civilian license plate on the car.
</P>
<P>
As before, we had no trouble this time passing the check point
near Labushnic, about 30 kilometers west of Pristina, because
Bozidar Filic, deputy chief of the Kosovo police department, was
with us as our guide. Along the road we ran into many such check
points, some so camouflaged that no one could recognize them until
being stopped.
</P>
<P>
Civilian vehicles were rare here, as most families had fled the
region ablaze with war flames since Serbian troops launched a
major offensive against the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) in late
July.
</P>
<P>
The hilltop we had passed, now under Serbian control at the
cost of two days of fierce fighting, overlooks a strategic road
linking Pristina with towns in western Kosovo -- once the KLA's
stronghold, but now a battlefield.
</P>
<P>
WESTERN KOSOVO DEVASTATED BY RAGING WARS
</P>
<P>
Imprints of war began to stimulate our view as we continued
westwards. Roads were littered with rocks and deserted vehicles,
once used as barricades by KLA fighters. Trenches crisscrossed the
hillsides, connecting numerous bastions which were strewn with
bread, canned food and beverage containers left by the KLA.
</P>
<P>
All the towns we passed were virtually no-go zones as violent
battles had driven residents to live with their relatives
elsewhere, to retreat with rebels to mountains, or to slip into
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Police guarding a hilltop bastion told us that 300 to 400 armed
Albanians holing up there had blocked the strategic road for two
months before it was taken back by the Serb security forces
following two days of fierce fighting.
</P>
<P>
Down from the hilltop, tanks and other armoured vehicles were
roaring on the narrow road. Water tankers escorted by armed police
were distributing water to police posts.
</P>
<P>
Filic told us that vehicles carrying no license plates were
police vehicles and their plates were removed out of fear of
Albanian snipers in the bushes.
</P>
<P>
In Malisevo, an abandoned town 45 kilometers west of Pristina,
the only sign of life we saw, apart from heavily armed Serbian
policemen, was a dog searching for food along an empty street.
</P>
<P>
No house was intact, many reduced to ruins, apparently the
result of heavy shelling. Cars were abandoned by the road sides,
their windows shattered and bodies riddled with bullet holes.
</P>
<P>
Reports said more than 200 people, many of them civilians, were
killed in the Kosovo conflicts, which have already displaced some
240,000 people and threaten to spill over to other parts of the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
New tolls are being reported on a daily basis as Serbian forces
push their lines into more KLA strongholds.
</P>
<P>
The KLA claimed more than one third of Kosovo following a
series of attacks earlier this year that met with little
resistance from Serb police.
</P>
<P>
"At first, we did not launch large-scale offensives out of
concern for civilians and international reaction," said Filic.
He said incessant KLA provocations finally spurred Serb police
into a rampage of counterattacks on July 25.
</P>
<P>
According to Serbian sources, government troops have regained
three-fourths of the land lost to the rebels, recapturing several
highways and forcing out the KLA headquarters.
</P>
<P>
In front of a two-story building that once housed the KLA
supreme command in Malisevo, a sign read: "No Photos."
</P>
<P>
"Please feel free to take photos," said Filic. "The sign was
the work of the KLA." He said the KLA command had retreated into
the mountains before Serbs arrived on July 30.
</P>
<P>
However, Filic did not allow us to travel further west because
fighting was still going on there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980815.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ... on there. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRISTINA TROUBLED BY RACIAL TENSION
</P>
<P>
Artillery was not heard back in Pristina, where babies in
prams were among those enjoying the evening cool in the central
square as onlookers almost forgot the increasing bloodshed of the
past five months in the war-torn province.
</P>
<P>
A group of children were frolicking in the square where both
the Serbian and Albanian tongue could be heard from young people
playing cards, and elderly women chatting about household
trivialities.
</P>
<P>
The atmosphere, however, was made grim by the sights of Serbian
policemen and police cars constantly patrolling the city, stopping
vehicles for identity checks.
</P>
<P>
A grey haired man strolling near the square told us, in
Serbian, that his family lived on tenterhooks as reports of
frontline clashes circulated in the city.
</P>
<P>
"Don't be deceived by the bustling city at this hour," he
said. "No one dares to stay on the street after 11 o'clock at
night."
</P>
<P>
He said many Serb families had moved out of Kosovo, but he was
still hesitant about leaving because he had lived and worked there
for more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo, bordered by Albania, has an area of 10,000 square
kilometers and a population of about two million, 90 percent
ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
Part of Yugoslavia since early this century, Kosovo has gripped
international attention since last February when armed ethnic
Albanians stepped up the guerrilla war for independence from
Serbia -- the dominant republic of the Yugoslav Federation.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Director of Pristina's Media Center Sinisa Rjepojevic
said Serb residents in the city were under increasing pressure as
hostility intensified between Serbs and Albanians along with the
ongoing strife.
</P>
<P>
As we dined at an outdoor restaurant run by an Albanian man,
the proprietor complained about the disproportionate share of
rights for the Albanian majority -- the root cause of the
separatist movement that has flared into armed rebellion.
</P>
<P>
The whole issue could be traced back to 1990 when Serbian
leader Slobodan Milosevic dismissed the Kosovo local parliament
and government. The move fueled the racial antagonism.
</P>
<P>
In the same year, Kosovo Albanian students and teachers went on
strike protesting the government's mandatory order to use the
unified curriculum designed by Serbian authorities.
</P>
<P>
Belgrade's concession to allow courses be taught in Albanian by
Albanian teachers in 1996, and an agreement last March to
implement the 1996 concession, was, however, not enough to pacify
the extreme separatists who took up armed rebellion anyway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980815.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ... rebellion anyway. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DEFERRING VIEWS ON POSSIBLE NATO INTERVENTION
</P>
<P>
NATO's repeated warnings of military intervention, a fond hope
of ethnic Albanian leaders, have so far failed to deter the
offensive of the Serbian government, which is always bitter about
foreign interference in its internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
In Kosovo, a prevailing view among the Serbs is that the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization has no right to send troops to their
homeland of generations.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo Information Bureau Director Bosko Drobnjak ruled out,
with confidence, the possibility of any NATO action. He noted that
NATO has declared its opposition to Kosovo's independence and
wanted a political solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said he saw no ground for NATO forces to step in as it
agreed with Belgrade on these essential matters.
</P>
<P>
Captain Vjestica Radomir, in charge of a Serbian checkpoint in
Komorane, said his men were not afraid of NATO military
threats. "If NATO dares to intrude, we will fight it to the end,"
Radomir said with a clenched fist.
</P>
<P>
In sharp contrast with Serbs' resentment against external
intervention, ethnic Albanian leaders insist that NATO military
action is needed to press Belgrade onto a political road to
resolve the problem.
</P>
<P>
Kol Berisa, second vice chairman of the Democratic Union of
Kosovo, the largest political party of ethnic Albanians, said that
only NATO's intervention, on the same level as that in the Bosnia
crisis, could force Belgrade to withdraw its troops from Kosovo
and sit down at the negotiation table.
</P>
<P>
He said the latest Serbian offensive proved the urgency for
strong international intervention.
</P>
<P>
"Actually, it is already too late for NATO to halt the
fighting," said Berisa with a grudge etched on his face.
</P>
<P>
While NATO's role in the Kosovo crisis remains disputable, the
international community is unanimous in appealing for an immediate
ceasefire and unconditional opening of dialogue between the
parties, on the basis of respect for the sovereignty and integrity
of Yugoslavia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980815.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ... of Yugoslavia. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUTURE LIES IN DIALOGUE
</P>
<P>
Where does the future of Kosovo lie? This is the question we
raised whenever we felt it was opportune during our short Kosovo
trip.
</P>
<P>
Answers were varied, with the majority of people advocating
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
"Our stance is clear-cut. That is, a political dialogue is the
only way out for Kosovo. Without preconditions, we are ever ready
for dialogue," Drobnjak said.
</P>
<P>
"We are willing to discuss with ethnic Albanians about the
highest-level autonomy which the international community could
recognize."
</P>
<P>
He said he believed that the most urgent issue was to sit down
and talk.
</P>
<P>
Zeliko Odalovic, supreme administrator of Kosovo, said: "We are
willing to have the dialogue resumed with the Albanian political
leaders on Kosovo autonomy, but we will never allow independence
or the status of republic which the international community will
not recognize either."
</P>
<P>
Many ethnic Albanians also favor a political solution to the
crisis. Even among the armed ethnic Albanians, moderate voices are
heard calling for a non-violent means to achieve Albanian
autonomy.
</P>
<P>
"The Democratic Union of Kosovo has always held that the Kosovo
issue should, and can only, be solved through dialogue," said
Berisa. "That was why we agreed to open talks with the Serbs. The
talks broke down when Serb authorities intensified their military
offensives."
</P>
<P>
Berisa said Serb authorities must halt their military
offensives and withdraw their troops from Kosovo before dialogue
can be resumed. He said he believed independence was the best
solution to the Kosovo situation.
</P>
<P>
As we drove back from Malisevo, fighting was still going on in
the western mountains. The big differences on the conditions for
dialogue has made it unlikely that talks will be resumed in the
near future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
