<HEADLINE> Polio Vaccination Campaign Starts in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A large vaccine campaign
in Somalia against polio started Saturday simultaneously in the
Somali capital and many regions in the central and southern
Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The campaign, sponsored by United Nation Children's Fund
(UNICEF) and World Health Organization (WHO) in collaboration
with Mogadishu's Joint Health Authority (JHA), is aimed at
immunizing more than 900,000 children under the age of five.
</P>
<P>
Faction leader Ali Mahdi Mohamed and other political and
religious leaders attended the ceremony for the inauguration of
the national immunization days held in north Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
According to Jeylani Mohamed Dini, the officer in-charge of
UNICEF-Mogadishu, the first phase of the campaign will last five
days starting at once in the central town of Dhusamareb to the
southern port town of Kismaio including the border region of
Gedo. In Mogadishu, more than 400 well trained people
are carrying out the campaign in 16 of its districts.
</P>
<P>
The motto of the campaign is to eradicate polio from the
earth surface by the year 2000 and the Somalis are informed not
to be the last victim of polio as happened during the eradication
campaign of the small box disease in 1977, when the last victim
of the small box all over the world happened to be a Somali man.
</P>
<P>
A group of youth with loud speakers have been circulating in
the streets of the capital since early Saturday morning, urging
the people, especially the mothers, to get their offsprings to the
nearest vaccine center for a free immunization.
</P>
<P>
More than 3,000 people supported by international
non-governmental organizations took in this campaign throughout
the central and southern Somalia Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In the coastal town of Merca, 100 km south of Mogadishu, the
Italian aid agency COSV had been operating in the polio
eradication campaign in its seven districts of Lower Shabelle
region.
</P>
<P>
Many of the mosques in Mogadishu and elsewhere in the country
had similarly taken their role in the social mobilization, urging
the people to get their children immunized against the polio
which is one of the six killer diseases of the children in the
world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
