<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan Worried About Escalation of Afghan War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Kazakh President Nursultan
Nazarbayev has expressed worry about the continued escalation of
conflicts in Afghanistan and warned all warring sides not to
spread fighting across the Afghan borders.
</P>
<P>
As reported by the Kazakh newspaper, Panorama Weekly, on
Saturday, Nazarbayev said the armed conflicts in northern
Afghanistan had lasted for 20 years and was now heading for the
southern borders of the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS).
</P>
<P>
The situation is worrisome, the president said.
</P>
<P>
He said he is consulting with leaders of other Central Asian
countries in hope of preventing the Afghan war from spreading
across the CIS borders.
</P>
<P>
Nazarbayev urged the Afghan warring factions to build a
peaceful country through negotiations instead of violent battles.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan had always stood solidly behind policies of keeping
Afghanistan's territorial integrity, and opposed any attempt at
interfering into its internal affairs, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan, in hope of the Afghan situation calming down, was
willing to set up normal and neighborly relations with the Pamir
nation, Nazarbayev said. 
