<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Call For Protection of Plant Genetic Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Several scientists warned here
today that one-eighth of the world's plant species are endangered
or threatened, and nearly 2,000 plant varieties are disappearing
every hour.
</P>
<P>
Kamaljit Bawa of the University of Massachusetts in the United
States, said here at the 18th International Congress of Genetics
that the annual deforestation rate between 1990 and 1995 was 13.4
million hectares, and that forest genetic resources are
diminishing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
He attributed this to loss of habitat and climatic changes, and
said that as a result of inadequate institutional and human
resources to deal with the problem, large amounts of plant genes
are being lost before they can be identified.
</P>
<P>
It will take a worldwide effort to protect plant genetic
resources, and people must make a choice, according to the social
and economic value of the plants, because they can not all be
protected at present, said Toby Hodgkin of the International Plant
Genetic Resources Institute.
</P>
<P>
In China, the loss of plant genetic resources is more serious,
and is not at present receiving close attention, according to Hong
Deyuan, director of the Institute of Botany of the Chinese Academy
of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Hong said that more than 90 percent of China's wild rice
species that existed in the early 1980s cannot be found
today. Wild rice species are genetic resources for high-yield and
good-quality hybrid rice.
</P>
<P>
China's well-known geneticist Tan Jiazhen urged the
establishment of germplasm banks and the use of modern
technologies, developed for gene mapping, cloning and sequencing
for the human genome project, to search for genes in cash crops
that have desirable traits.
</P>
<P>
"Humans, plants and animals are inter-dependent," said
Professor Bawa, adding that "Protecting them is protecting
ourselves." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980815.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Siberian Tigers Well-cared-of Under Flood Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The roaring water of the Songhua
River is constantly weakening the dikes, but the life of the 52
Siberian tigers living in the world's large zoo of such creatures
400 meters from the river are as peaceful as usual.
</P>
<P>
Visitors who brave the heavy rain to the zoo are really relaxed
and pleased. But Liu Xinchen, the zoo's director, knows well how
narrowly these precious tigers have escaped the hazards of one of
the worst flood in Harbin, capital of northeast China's
Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
"If not for the round-the-clock anti-flood efforts, the zoo
would have been totally submerged by water," he said.
</P>
<P>
On 6:00 pm, August 11, a 120-meter-long levee near the zoo
suddenly caved in. Without timely efforts, the water might quickly
rush to the zoo.
</P>
<P>
With a strong sense of protecting the endangered species, over
50 zoo staffs rushed to the scene in no time, who were joined by
soldiers of a nearby armed police school. The blocking took seven
hours to complete.
</P>
<P>
The situation of the tigers aroused the concern of the whole
city. While the city government contributed 300,000 yuan
(36,000 US dollars) of special funds, much more were donated from
tiger lovers.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Chengzhong, a staff of the zoo, has been taking care of
the tigers for four days running without going back home, though
his home is constantly threatened by the flood.
</P>
<P>
"I can build another home if it is lost. But if the tiger is
lost, nothing will make up for it," he said.
</P>
<P>
There are about 300 Siberian tigers living in the wild in the
world, mainly in northeast China and Russia. The species is on the
world's list of ten endangered species.
</P>
<P>
A Siberian tiger breeding center was set up in 1986 as part of
China's efforts to increase the number of the precious
creature. Over 100 tigers have been bred since then. The zoo in
Harbin was built in 1996.
</P>
<P>
By 15:00 today, water at the Harbin section of the Songhua
River rose to 119.36 meters, 0.36 meter higher than the safety
mark.
</P>
<P>
"We are all set to move the tigers to safe places whenever
necessary," said Liu Xinchen.  
</P>
</TEXT>
