<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolian President Rejects PM Nomination Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Mongolian President Nachagyn
Bagabandy repeated on Saturday that he did not agree on the
nomination of Davaadorj Ganbold as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The leadership of the ruling union, the Mongolian National
Democratic Party and Social Democratic Party, had once asked
Bagabandy, on Friday, to submit Ganbold's nomination to the Great
Hural (parliament), a presidential spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Bagabandy insisted that the ruling union made another
nomination, strictly observing legal procedures, the spokesman
added.
</P>
<P>
Bagabandy first rejected the nomination early this month, as he
believed that Ganbold, the Great Hural Standing Committee of
Economic Policy Chairman, was responsible for the country's
intensified banking crisis.
</P>
<P>
A decision in May to merge the state Renovation Bank with the
private Golomt Bank resulted in the dismissal of Prime Minister
Tsakhya Elbegdorj's government in July.
</P>
<P>
President Bagabandy believed that Ganbold failed in his duty of
overseeing or preventing the merger. The Great Hural Friday
withdrew the merger decision.
</P>
<P>
Under Mongolia's law, the ruling party's parliamentary group
should discuss the nomination for prime minister with the
president, who in turn submits it to the Great Hural for
approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
