<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Balance of Payment Records Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's balance on the
current account had a turnaround from persistent deficits since
the fourth quarter of 1992 to a large surplus of 6.6 billion
ringgit (about 1.578 billion U.S. dollars) in the first quarter of
1998, according to the Department of Statistics Saturday.
</P>
<P>
This surplus was attributed to the surge in earnings from
merchandise exports free on board (f.o.b), which, according to the
figures released by the Department, increased by 5.7 percent in
the first quarter of 1998 to hit 69.1 billion ringgit (about
16.531 billion U.S. dollars) against 65.4 billion ringgit (about
15.645 million U.S. dollars) in the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
Merchandise imports f.o.b., on the other hand, dropped by 4.6
percent to 57.6 billion ringgit (about 13.779 billion U.S.
dollars) from 60.4 billion ringgit (about 14.449 billion U.S.
dollars) in the fourth quarter 1997.
</P>
<P>
Hence, the country's merchandise trade surplus was boosted to a
record high of 11.5 billion ringgit (about 2.751 billion U.S.
dollars) in the quarter under the review.
</P>
<P>
An improvement was also evident in the services account deficit
which narrowed to 4.1 billion ringgit (about 1 billion U.S.
dollars) (-31.7 percent) over the previous quarter, owing to an
improved position in the following components such as investment
income, where net outflows declined by 8.3 percent to 3.3 billion
ringgit (about 789.473 million U.S. dollars); freight and
insurance where net outlay reduced by 14.8 percent to 2.3 billion
ringgit (about 550.239 million U.S. dollars); and other services
which recorded a surplus of 0.3 billion ringgit (about 71.77
million U.S. dollars) from 1.3 billion ringgit (about 311 million
U.S. dollars) deficit in the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, the other transportation and travel and education
components continued to reflect a surplus position, albeit a
smaller one, in the first quarters, the Statistics Department
said.
</P>
<P>
However, net freight and insurance payments widened to 2.3
billion ringgit (about 550 million U.S. dollars) in the quarter
under review from 2.0 billion ringgit (about 478.468 million U.S.
dollars) in the first quarter 1997.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, net long-term capital inflow fell sharply by 72.2
percent to 1.5 billion ringgit (about 358.851 million U.S.
dollars) in the first quarter this year from 5.4 billion ringgit
(about 1.291 billion U.S. dollars) achieved in the
October-December quarter 1997.
</P>
<P>
The reduced net long-term capital inflow was largely due to the
factors such as the reduction of 37.8 percent to 2.8 billion
ringgit (about 669.856 million U.S. dollars) in net inflow for net
private long-term capital from the October-December 1997 inflow of
4.5 billion ringgit (about 1.076 billion U.S. dollars) and a net
outflow of 1.3 billion ringgit (about 311 million U.S. dollars) in
January-March 1998 quarter for net official long-term capital
compared to a net inflow of 0.9 billion ringgit (about 215.311
million U.S. dollars) in October-December 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
Reflecting the outcome on the current and capital accounts, the
basic balance, amounting to 8.0 billion ringgit (about 1.913
billion U.S. dollars) in the first quarter of 1998, was higher
than the level of 3.5 billion ringgit (about 837.32 million U.S.
dollars) achieved in the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
The international reserves of Bank Negara (State Bank) Malaysia
concomitantly registered a decline of 1.9 billion ringgit (about
454.545 million U.S. dollars) in the first quarter 1998 as against
a decline of 2.8 billion ringgit (about 669.856 billion U.S.
dollars) in the previous quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
