<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More FBI Agents to Search Bombing Evidence in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 15 (Xinhua) - More agents of the Federal
Bureau of Investigation (FBI) of the United States will join
their counterparts in searching clues leading to perpetrators of
the deadly bomb attack on the U.S. Embassy in the Tanzanian
capital last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Kenneth Piernick, head of the FBI team here, told reporters in
front of the damaged embassy premises Saturday that some
important evidences collected at the scene have been sent back to
Washington for analysis.
</P>
<P>
Piernick, who is the Assistant Special Agent in charge of the
FBI Washington Field Office, said nothing could be found from the
video monitoring system at the embassy, which was working at the
time when the bomb went off, because there was no tape working in
the system.
</P>
<P>
"On behalf of the FBI, I want to ensure the people of
Tanzania, the people of Kenya and the United States that we are
dedicated to identify the perpetrators of these attacks," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Piernick said that a total of more than 200 FBI agents are
cooperating with their Kenyan and Tanzanian counterparts in the
bombings investigation at present and that the premises of the U.S.
embassy in Dar es Salaam have been combed, finding no more
remains of the bombing victims.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Director of Criminal Investigation Adadi Rajabu also
told the reporters that search for the whereabout of an assistant
driver of the water tanker, believed to be planted with a bomb
which killed nine Tanzanians and one Kenyan and wounding more
than 80 civilians, was well underway.
</P>
<P>
Rajabu said police have so far found nothing related to the
co-driver of the Embassy's truck, a blue 7-ton Toyota water
tanker, which he believed to be the key to the investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
