<HEADLINE> Pak Denies Providing Military Assistance to Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Saturday denied
allegations that the country has provided military assistance to
the Islamic Taliban in their recent strong offensives in northern
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"This is motivated propaganda, it also flies in the face of
reality," a Foreign Office spokesman told a weekly news briefing
here in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan has not militarily assisted or interfered in
Afghanistan," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is ironical that a campaign of deliberate distortion on the
situation in Afghanistan has been launched against Pakistan," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We are not only deeply disappointed but we resent that some
countries are making accusations against Pakistan without paying
heed to our clear reiteration of non-involvement and
non-interference in Afghanistan," he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Pakistan believes that the international
community should "dispassionately look at the situation in
Afghanistan and accept the realities on the ground."
</P>
<P>
He said the international community should engage with Taliban
so as to encourage them to preserve with their declared domestic
agenda which "is purely domestic and pose no threat to any
neighboring country."
</P>
<P>
In their latest attempt to take over the whole Afghanistan, the
hard-line Taliban militia have overrun Mazar-e-Sharif,
headquarters of the rival northern alliance, and a few other
strategic northern bases over the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Russia, Iran and the Afghan opposition have accused Pakistan of
giving military aid to the Taliban. 
</P>
</TEXT>
