<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian House of
Representatives (DPR) Speaker Harmoko Saturday urged the
government to thoroughly investigate the mid-May mass rape and
looting cases.
</P>
<P>
"It is our hope that the Joint Fact-finding Team formed by the
government recently will be able to uncover the cases
transparently so that the positive image of the nation's character
can be restored," Harmoko said in a speech marking the opening of
the House's first session for the 1998-99 period.
</P>
<P>
The House plenary session which was attended by all members of
DPR and the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR), was also
addressed by President B.J. Habibie to mark the commemoration of
Indonesia's 53rd Independence Day.
</P>
<P>
Harmoko said on the aspect of realizing the democratic
tradition, a comprehensive solution of the cases considered
important for the order of democracy should guarantee the rights
of all citizens, including the minority.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that more than 2,000 people were killed and
over 5,000 shops and homes damaged or burnt as well as 170 women
were raped during the may 13-15 riots in Jakarta and some other
cities.
</P>
<P>
Harmoko said it is high time for Indonesian people to put the
democratic approach and people's welfare in front.
</P>
<P>
The government was expected to be able to solve every problem
that emerges comprehensively, he added. 
</P>
