<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Deputy PM Calls for Teamwork in Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim Saturday called for teamwork and full
support by all sectors in achieving economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, who is also finance minister, said at a forum here that
the prevalent political stability would have to be preserved so
that recovery from the current economic problems could
materialize.
</P>
<P>
"Political stability demands inter-racial harmony," he said,
adding it was incumbent upon the younger generation to preserve
racial harmony, a prerequisite in ensuring a future for the
country.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said Malaysia would have to be prepared to tackle the
economic problems on its own without help from Western countries
which he said would obviously be inconsiderate and unsympathetic
to Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has to take full charge in steering its economy out of
the present crisis, without depending on foreign assistance, he
said, adding with bigger Asian economies like Japan, South Korea
and China grappling with their own economic problems, Malaysia had
no countries to turn to for assistance.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said that when rich countries demanded that developing
countries have greater transparency, they must also do the same
especially to their hedge funds and currency trading.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said the claim that the financial meltdown erupted in
Asia because all the regional economies were fundamentally weak
and flawed could not be true.
</P>
<P>
He said the problems were actually due to the world financial
system which lacked transparency and full disclosure of the hedge
funds.
</P>
<P>
He said that while Malaysia wants the world financial system to
be improved, it is not resting on its laurels, and that is why the
government has taken steps to rejuvenate the economy according to
its own set agenda.
</P>
<P>
Anwar also said that the government has accepted the fact that
it would take time for the country's economy to recover but with
resilience and the ability to ward off personal grudges and social
tension, the country's economy could be revived. 
</P>
</TEXT>
