<HEADLINE> Power-Sharing Concept to Continue in Malaysia's Sabah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad pledged Saturday the power-sharing concept
practiced by the ruling Barisan Nasional (BN) (National Front) in
the state of Sabah, East Malaysia, will proceed for as long as the
people in the state want it to go on.
</P>
<P>
The power-sharing concept was proposed by Mahathir, who is also
BN Chairman, during the run-up to the state election in February
1994 to provide an opportunity for a representative of the Muslim
Bumiputeras (aborigines), the Chinese and non-Muslim Bumiputeras
in the state to head the state government.
</P>
<P>
The concept, whereby the post of chief minister of the state is
rotated among the three major communities in the state, has
proceeded smoothly after the state election with all the BN
component parties giving their cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The first under the rotation system to hold the chief
minister's post was Tun Sakaran Dandai of United Malays National
Organization (UMNO) representing Muslim Bumiputeras from March
1994 who was replaced by Salleh Tun Said in December the same year
when Sakaran was appointed the Governor of the state.
</P>
<P>
Yong Teck Lee, representing the Chinese community, took over
the post in May 1996 and he was replaced by Dompok, who represents
the non-Muslim Bumiputera community, on May 28, this year.
</P>
<P>
"The rotation system will continue unless they (the Sabahans)
themselves feel that it is no longer necessary to do so," Mahathir
told a news conference in Kota Kinabalu, Sabah's capital, before
leaving for Kuala Lumpur after a three-day visit to the state and
the nearby Federal Territory of Labuan, according to Malaysia's
national news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir made the pledge at a time when the Sabah state whose
next election is due by March next year is preparing for an early
state election. Mahathir confirmed in an exclusive interview with
Xinhua news agency Thursday that Sabah would go for an early state
election, but without specifying the date.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, when asked for comment on the chances
of BN's victory in the next state election, Mahathir said that at
present there was strong unity in the BN which comprises 14
parties and if this could be maintained there was a good chance of
the BN winning the election.
</P>
<P>
In Sabah, there are nine BN component parties. Mahathir said
that all the BN component parties in Sabah could propose the names
of their candidates to be fielded in the state election but he
would make the final decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
