<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Rally to End Volatile Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LONDON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- European shares rallied on Friday
after Hong Kong staged a powerful rebound and Moscow vowed not to
devaluate the rouble, ending a highly volatile week which wiped 3
percent off Europe's biggest stock markets.
</P>
<P>
Friday's rally came on the coat-tails of an 8.5 percent
advance in Hong Kong stocks and a 13.7 percent gain in Russia.
Both markets slumped on Thursday as investors focused on
devaluation risks. In addition, a steady yen helped calm
international investors' nerves.
</P>
<P>
In London, the FTSE 100 climbed 55.5 to 5,455.0, but was unable
to hold onto the 5,500 level after reaching a high of 5517.6. The
index lost 225.4 points or 3.97 percent on the week.
</P>
<P>
While oil issues performed well, banking stocks were the main
beneficiaries, with takeover talk adding spice. HSBC and Lloyds TSB
were described as potential partners while reports linking JP Morgan
with an approach from Deutsche Bank boosted the Dow Jones, according
to market sources.
</P>
<P>
Looking to next week, however, traders said that even if
international markets calmed down, there was still a heavy week of
UK data, including inflation and sales figures, to deal with.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfort, the Xetra-Dax rose just over 2 percent at
5,473.72. Shares in Deutsche Bank rose more than 5 percent on
rumors it is in preliminary talks with a major Wall Street firm,
with dealers speculating it had approached JP Morgan.
</P>
<P>
However, traders warned that a close watch was being kept on
developments in Russia, saying that the market would be looking for
signs that German banks could suffer from Russia's continued
financial problems amid concerns about the stability of the rouble.
</P>
<P>
Paris stocks close up over 1 percent, buoyed by Dow rally, but
trade lacked conviction as buyers fretted over Asia.
</P>
<P>
The CAC-40 index closed up 43.22 points at 3,994.91 but were
down 1.16 percent on the week overall.
</P>
<P>
The European markets' gains Friday were small in the context of
recent losses. Since reaching all-time highs four-weeks ago, the
FTSE and DAX have fallen around 12 percent and the CAC more than
9 percent. The Dow, which has led the bull market for three and a
half years, has also fallen more than 9 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
