<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pediatrician Convicted in Xinjiang Medical Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A pediatrician whose dereliction
of duty resulted in the death of an eight-year-old girl has been
sentenced to two years in jail and made to pay compensation of
100,000 yuan, by a court in Urumqi, capital of northwest China's
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The 30-year-old pediatrician, Ding Jie, is the first doctor
convicted of a medical crime in Xinjiang since a law related to
medical practices was added to the amendments to China's Criminal
Law last year.
</P>
<P>
Ding made a simple examination of the girl, Tang Yunlu, who had
a fever and headache, on August 20, 1996, and decided to
hospitalize her in the pediatric ward.
</P>
<P>
After an injection of penicillin, the girl's temperature
remained high. When the girl's parents proposed looking for a more
experienced doctor or transfering her to another hospital, Ding
replied, "let's wait till tomorrow," and he then left.
</P>
<P>
In the small hours of the next morning, under repeated requests
from the girl's parents, Ding prescribed aspirin for the girl who
began to twitch after this treatment, and subsequently died at
10:25 am.
</P>
<P>
The relevant departments of the city of Urumqi and the
Autonomous Region assessed this case as a class-one medical
incident, and the court of the Tianshan District, Urumqi,
sentenced Ding to the prison term and ordered him to pay the huge
compensation.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Ding has lodged an appeal to a higher
court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980815.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> National Road Gives Way to Stone Buddhas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, August 15 (Xinhua) -- A project to relocate a section
of National Highway No.109 is under way as part of an effort to
protect over 50,000 stone Buddhas at the Yungang Grottos in north
China's Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The section, part of the highway linking Beijing with Lhasa,
capital of the Tibet Autonomous Region, currently fronts the
entrance to the grottos. The over 10,000 coal trucks using the
main transportation artery on a daily basis have churned out large
quantities and sulphur dioxide which created a grave threat to the
stone Buddhas.
</P>
<P>
The grottoes, located on the southern slopes of Wuzhou Mountain
to the west of Datong, are surrounded by dozens of coal mines with
a combined annual output of over 10 million tons. The existing
highway section was located withing 300 meters of the ancient
cultural site.
</P>
<P>
Air pollution tests show that the dust content in the area
surpasses the state standard by a factor of 27-fold. Acid rain
represents yet another major threat to the stone Buddhas.
</P>
<P>
"The project represents the first time that China has relocated
a major national highway to protect a cultural relics site,"
according to Li Zhiguo, director of the Yungang Grottos Cultural
Relics Research Center.
</P>
<P>
The 25.8-km project will be completed at a cost of 188 million
yuan (22.9 million US dollars) and will add to the total length
for the original section. Plans call for completion of the project
by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Work on the Yungang Grottos commenced in the latter part of the
4th century, with over 10,000 skilled craftsmen working over 60
years to complete the project. Forty-five caves and 252 niches
hold more than 51,000 stone Buddhas, the largest of which stands
17 meters in height and smallest a mere 0.02 meter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980815.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Evacuated Residents Return as Dike Burst Plugged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JIUJIANG, August 15 (Xinhua) -- People are drying up their
clothing and other belongings under the sun, while the smells and
sounds of cooking are stirring the air.
</P>
<P>
Residents were moving back to their homes in the western
suburbs in Jiujiang, in east China's Jiangxi Province, as the work
to plug a 60 m-burst in the dike of the Yangtze River close to
their houses finally came to its end on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In the first days of the breach, which occurred on August 7,
several thousand tons of rice and soybeans, a large amount of
rock, a truck, and eight boats loaded with rock or coal were
dumped into the breach but failed to block the rushing water.
</P>
<P>
It was finally blocked, on Wednesday, by thousands of soldiers
including a special experts team from the army, with a technology
developed to build bridges in the war time.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three days, people have used 4,000 square meters
of special clay to seal off any leakage in the repaired dike. Some
35,000 square meters of rock are expected to be used to reinforce
it in the coming days, officials in charge of the work said.
</P>
<P>
However, local experts said they will continue patroling around
the 150 kilometer-long city embankments to prevent any possible
burst.
</P>
<P>
No one was killed in the burst, but it has attracted wide
attention from home and abroad. It has been the first burst of the
embankments along the mainstream of the Yangtze since 1954,
according to an expert from the Yangtze River Water Conservancy
Committee.
</P>
<P>
Jiujiang, with a population of 500,000 and an area of 30 square
kilometers, is a major industrial and tourist city in Jiangxi. The
city embankments breached in 1954 when a deluge devastated many
localities along the Yangtze, killing over 33,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
