<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Apologizes to Victims of Abuses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie conveyed here on Saturday his government's apologies to
the people who became victims of human rights violations by the
former government apparatus in May in Jakarta and other cities of
the country.
</P>
<P>
"On behalf of the government, I would like to express my
deepest regrets for human rights violations in several regions.
Hereby, I apologize to the Indonesian people in particular to the
families of the victims," Habibie said in his address of state
before the House of the People's Representatives on the occasion
of the 53rd Independence Day which falls on August 17.
</P>
<P>
The riots, in the form of looting and burning of shopping
centers and people's houses, were even aggravated by the violence
and sexual harassment against women, mostly the ethnic Chinese,
said the president.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that more than 2,000 people were killed and
over 5,000 shops and homes damaged or burnt as well as 170 women
were raped during the May 13-15 riots in the capital city and some
other cities.
</P>
<P>
The president said all of these irresponsible acts are indeed
very disgraceful. "They have streaked the face of our nation, a
nation renowned for its good character and high morals, with
shame. As a civilized and religious nation, we curse these
barbaric acts," he added.
</P>
<P>
All of the nation feel concerned over the cases of human rights
violation against the dignity and honor of the citizens and the
mankind, Habibie said.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, the leadership of Indonesian Armed Forces (ABRI)
is thoroughly investigating the case, he said.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to ask all parties, in particular community and
religious leaders to support and trust ABRI and also to give it as
ample opportunity as possible to investigate the case," Habibie
said.
</P>
<P>
The government and ABRI's leaders have asserted that such a
case shall never happen again in the future, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
