<HEADLINE> People Evacuated After Second Dike Breach Near Largest Oilfield </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Daqing, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Most of the some 3,850 people
besieged by flood-water after a dike of the Nenjiang River
breached early this morning have been evacuated to safe places.
</P>
<P>
The 20-meter breach of a 2.7 kilometer levee in Zhaoyuan County
near China's largest oilfield of Daqing inundated 13,333 hectares
of farmland of a nearby farm. The water, if not effectively
blocked, will pose a threat to the oilfield and a railway.
</P>
<P>
It is the second dike breach near Daqing. The first, measuring
500 meters wide, occurred at 6:00 am on August 14.
</P>
<P>
The repair of both of the breaches have been given up. Now the
the effort is focused on fortifying the secondary and the third
dikes protecting Daqing City, local sources said.
</P>
<P>
Heavy waterlogging has already inundated 355 oil wells and
reduced the daily production of the Daqing Oilfields by 807
tons. But most of the 20,000 wells are still operating normally,
according to earlier reports.
</P>
<P>
Located in northeast China's Heilongjiang Province, Daqing Oil
Fields turned out 60.9 million tons of crude oil in 1997,
accounting for half of the country's output. 
</P>
</TEXT>
