<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 09:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey to Be Tougher on Islamic Clout in School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's Higher Education Board
(YOK) is to appoint new university presidents who will not allow
head-scarfed female students into campus and will refuse to
register them if they submit photos wearing headscarves.
</P>
<P>
The Daily News newspaper reported Saturday that this is part of
the efforts by Turkey's secularist institutions to curb Islamist
influence in public places.
</P>
<P>
Wearing headscarves is not illegal, but if done in public
places such as schools and hospitals, it constitutes a "crime" is
punishable by disciplinary action in the predominantly Muslim, but
politically secular country, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The YOK will appoint 20 new university presidents in November
and will take into consideration the backgrounds of the candidates
nominated by the universities.
</P>
<P>
The new presidents will be strictly warned not to tolerate
head-scarfed students entering their schools, to move ahead with
disciplinary action against female students who insist on veiling
their heads, or to expel them if necessary.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, education officials in Ankara launched an
investigation into two religious Imam-Hatip high schools, where
female teachers are wearing headscarves while teaching.
</P>
<P>
The officials said they will take measures against the
principals who allowed teachers to veil their heads in class.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980815.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian People Urged to Restore Self-Confidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie Saturday urged the people to restore their self-confidence
which he said was the key to the country's recovery from its
prolonged economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
"As soon as confidence is restored, I am very sure that
Indonesia will stand up again, faster than other countries which
have been hit by a similar crisis," he said when speaking before
members of the House of the People's Representatives (DPR) on the
occasion of the 53rd anniversary of Indonesia's National
Independence which falls on August 17.
</P>
<P>
All components of the country needed to look at the abundant
natural resources which were waiting to be tapped to yield quick
revenues.
</P>
<P>
"The key to our endeavor to emerge from the present crisis is
to restore confidence, namely the confidence of domestic and
foreign economic actors and, more importantly, confidence in
ourselves," Habibie said.
</P>
<P>
Since the country was hit by the monetary crisis, its economy
has been projected to contract by up to 15 percent this year, its
banking system almost collapsed and its international image
damaged.
</P>
<P>
On his government's strategy to end the crisis which hit
Indonesia since mid-1997, Habibie said his administration would
keep on focusing on four main points of what he called "economic
stabilization and reform programs."
</P>
<P>
The four main points gave high priority to the straightening up
of the country's financial institutions; solving problems relating
to the private sector's debts; making the country more efficient
and competitive by eliminating monopolistic practices; and
promoting openness and transparency in governance and in business
management.
</P>
<P>
Openness and transparency in the two areas were important to
wipe out the country's chronic illnesses: corruption, collusion
and nepotism, he explained.
</P>
<P>
Reforms in the financial sector were needed, because no modern
economy could operate without the support of a well-functioning
and reputable banking system, the president said.
</P>
<P>
To settle the cases of insolvent banks, the Indonesian Banking
Restructuring Agency had taken over the management of 55 banks, he
said, adding that some of the ailing banks' share ownership had
also been taken over.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, international confidence in and support for
Indonesia was now strong as was evident from the fact that the
country with more than 200 million population would receive about
14 billion U.S. dollars in foreign financial assistance.
</P>
<P>
"This amount (of money) can be wholly disbursed within this
fiscal year to sustain our budget and balance of payments," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Habibie, who replaced former president Soeharto after the
latter resigned on May 21 this year, urged the Indonesians not to
feel desperate or pessimistic.
</P>
<P>
"Let us shoulder together in all sincerity and seriousness the
grand task of ushering our nation and state into the twenty-first
century," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
