<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Not to Use Nuclear Weapons Against Others: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Atal
Behari Vajpayee Saturday said that India would never use nuclear
weapons for aggression.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the nation from the ramparts of Red Fort here on the
occasion of the country's 51st Independence Day, Vajpayee said
that no power on earth could force India to change from its
pre-determined path of global disarmament.
</P>
<P>
India conducted five underground nuclear tests in mid-May this
year causing great concern the world over. Pakistan, tit-for-tat,
also conducted six nuclear tests at the end of May casting a new
shadow over the bilateral relations between the two neighboring
countries and aggravating tension in the South Asian region.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee said that he looked forward to meeting his Pakistani
counterpart Nawaz Sharif again in Durban of South Africa on the
fringes of the Non-Aligned Summit to carry forward the process of
bilateral dialogue between India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee's first meeting with Sharif on the sidelines of the
summit of the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation
(SAARC) in Colombo, Sri Lanka, on July 29-31 failed due to the
dispute over the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that there is no dispute which cannot be resolved
through a dialogue," Vajpyee said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to economic issues, Vajpayee asserted that the
government was determined to make India an economic superpower in
the coming years. He said that India had the potential to play a
leading role in developing information technology and new steps
would be taken in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Though swadeshi (self-reliance) did not mean insulating India
from outside world, no body would be allowed to take undue
advantage of liberalization in the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
He identified rising prices and corruption at high places as
two major problems facing the country and expressed his
government's resolve to address them on high priority.
</P>
<P>
Incessant rains dampened Saturday's celebrations with a thin
crowd turning out to hear Vajpayee's speech, canceling also the
aerobatics planned by the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
Drenched school children who gathered on the rain-soaked ground
since early morning and security personnel outnumbered the general
public at the annual event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
