<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eight Japanese Ministers Visit Yasukuni Shrine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Eight ministers of the Japanese
government visited Tokyo's Yasukuni Shrine Saturday to pay respects to
Japan's criminals on the 53rd anniversary of the country's surrender in
World War II.
</P>
<P>
The eight included Transport Minister Jiro Kawasaki,
Posts and Telecommunications Minister Seiko Noda, Labor Minister
Akira Amari and Chief of the Management and Coordination Agency
Seiichi Ota.
</P>
<P>
Five other cabinet members also visited the shrine some time
before Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, Chief Cabinet Secretary
Hiromu Nonaka and six other ministers have said they would not
visit the shrine.
</P>
<P>
Japanese cabinet members' visit to the shrine, a bastion of the
wartime military government-sponsored Shintoism and symbol of
militarism in Japan before and during World War II, often draw
criticism from Japan's neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
The shrine houses the memorial tablets of 14 class-A war criminals,
including wartime prime minister Hideki Tojo, and some 2.4 million
Japanese military personnel and officials who died since 1853 in
Japan's various wars.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet ministers' visit to the Shrine is also controversial
as Japan's postwar constitution stipulates separation of religion
and the state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
