<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Expresses Remorse For Wartime Acts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi Saturday expressed "deep remorse" for Japan's wartime acts
in Asia and extended condolences to war victims in neighboring
Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
"That war caused tremendous pain and sorrow particularly to
Asian neighboring countries. We would like to express our deep
regret and condolences to them sincerely," Obuchi said in an
address at a government-sponsored ceremony marking the 53rd
anniversary of Japan's surrender in World War II.
</P>
<P>
This is the sixth consecutive year in which Japan's Prime
Ministers have expressed remorse toward Asian war victims in their
speeches in the annual event.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi also pledged in his speech to make all-out effort to
maintain a permanent peace.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Emperor Akihito and Empress Michiko, along with some
5,800 relatives of the dead in the Japanese war and about 1,000
government officials and lawmakers, attended the ceremony held at
Nippon Budokan hall in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the ceremony observed one minute's silence in
honor of the souls of some 3.1 million Japanese who died in the
war.
</P>
<P>
In a brief memorial address delivered after the silent tribute,
Emperor Akihito extended condolences to the dead and prayed for
world peace, saying that "looking back at history, I pray from the
heart that the ravages of War will never be repeated." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
