<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 06:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's Half-Year Tourism Income up by 5 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The income of Jordan's tourism
industry reached 244 million U.S. dollars in the first half of
this year, a 5 percent increase over the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Aqel Biltaji, minister of tourism and antiquities, attributed
the increase to more tourists from the Arab Gulf states.
</P>
<P>
He said the number of such tourists recorded a 36 percent rise
in the first seven months of this year from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
About 351,000 Saudi Arabians and 58,000 Kuwaitis came to
Jordan in pursuit of breeze and cool, out of a total of 444,000
tourists arriving in the kingdom during the period, he told the
official Radio Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The increase of tourism income could also be attributed to
longer stay by the tourists in Jordan, Biltaji said.
</P>
<P>
Each tourist had an average of 4.18 days of stay in Jordan in
the first four months of this year, compared with 3.9 days in the
same period of 1997, he added.
</P>
<P>
The tourism income in the first half of this year would have
been much higher, if the the number of tourists from Europe and
the United States had not suffered a 19 percent decrease, he said.
</P>
<P>
Regional political uncertainty, arising from Israel's hardline
policy on the Arab world and Iraq's brief stand-off with the
United Nations in February, kept away European and U.S. visitors.
</P>
<P>
The number of German tourists decreased by 41 percent,
Austrians by 39.5 percent, Finnish by 27 percent, Britons 24
percent and Swiss by 23 percent in the first seven months of the
year from the same period of 1997, he said.
</P>
<P>
Tourism has been Jordan's pillar industry. Before the Gulf
crisis (1990-91), its annual income usually reached above 500
million Jordanian dinars (about 706 million dollars), or 37
percent of its annual foreign currency earnings and 11 percent
of its gross domestic products.
</P>
<P>
However, the instability in the region in recent years hurt the
industry and its income was down by a big margin.
</P>
<P>
Arab Gulf nationals used to have months-long holidays out of
their countries to escape sweltering summer heat and most of them
would like to spend a few days in Jordan, which boasted summer
breeze and cool.
</P>
<P>
European and U.S. tourists often bought package tours in the
Middle East and included Jordan as one of their favorite stops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980815.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Budget Deficit Sees July Setback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's budget deficit in July
went for the first time this year beyond the overall 42 percent
target for 1998, marking a setback from performance in previous
months, the Daily Star reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In its monthly report issued on Friday, the Finance Ministry
said that the deficit rose from 33 percent in June to 51 percent
last month.
</P>
<P>
Expenditures increased from 427 million U.S. dollars in June
to 492 million dollars, including 219 million dollars for
debt-servicing, while revenues dropped to 243 million dollars
from 288 million dollars, leaving a budget gap of 249 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
For the first seven months of the year, the report said,
expending reached 2.82 billion dollars, including 1.27 billion
dollars in debt-servicing.
</P>
<P>
Revenues only reached 1.76 billion dollars, leaving a deficit
of 1.06 billion dollars, or 38 percent, an improvement on the 50
percent reached at the end of the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Excluding debt servicing, the government achieved a primary
surplus of 200 million dollars for the first seven months of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Huge annual budget deficits has helped push the national debt
over 15.5 billion dollars, an estimated 100 percent of the
national income.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Finance Minister Fuad Sinyoura as saying that
the July setback has not affected the government's optimism about
achieving its 1998 budget deficit target.
</P>
<P>
"We are warning everybody that revenues and expenditures
fluctuate from month to month," he said, adding "We have revenues
that have not been transferred yet."
</P>
<P>
He also believed that the drop in revenues from the Ministry of
Post and Telecommunications, which is considered by the government
as a main national income source, contributed to the increase in
deficit.
</P>
<P>
Local economists said that although the July setback is higher
than figures in recent months, the government is still on course
to achieve its target. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
