<HEADLINE> Unique Museum Of Seal Carving In Eastern Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The city of Hangzhou, the
capital of east China's Zhejiang Province, is planning on building
a museum of seal carving later this month near the popular tourist
spot, West Lake.
</P>
<P>
The museum is affiliated with the Xiling Seal-Engravers Club,
which was founded in 1896 as the first club of its kind devoted
entirely to the study and practice of the ancient Chinese art of
seal-carving. The club has members in China, Japan, Korea,
Singapore, Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The museum design will include memorial rooms dedicated to the
memory of some prominent engravers, one of whom is Wu Changshuo,
an artist and one of the founders of the club. It will also have a
room that tells the club's history.
</P>
<P>
There will also be a gallery where different types of seals are
exhibited. Thousands of materials related to seal making, bronze
and stone inscriptions, paintings, calligraphy, and manuscripts of
famous experts will be on display.
</P>
<P>
Financing will come from the state and the city of Hangzhou.
Its cost is estimated at 10 million yuan (1.2 million US
dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
