<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flooding Affects Production of Largest Oilfield </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAQING, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Waterlogging caused by heavy
floods had inundated 355 oil wells of China's largest oilfield of
Daqing by 20:00 of August 14, partially knocking off the
production.
</P>
<P>
Figures show that the inundation has reduced the daily crude
oil output by 807 tons. But most of the oilfield's nearly 20,000
wells are said to be operating normally.
</P>
<P>
Located in northeast China's Heilongjiang Province, Daqing
Oilfield produced a total of 60.9 million tons of oil in 1997,
accounting for half of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
Daqing City, with a population of 2.34 million, has been under
the threat of one of the worst flooding of the Nenjiang River.
</P>
<P>
The State Flood Control and Drought Relief Headquarters and the
provincial government are allocating two million sandbags and
other materials and large quantities of relief goods for
Daqing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980815.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean President Proposes New Dialogue with DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 15 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim
Dae-jung Saturday proposed a ministerial-level dialogue forum with
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to mark the 50th anniversary of the founding of the
nation on Saturday morning, Kim said the proposal was made in the
spirit of hope of removing the "wall of distrust" and promoting
bilateral exchanges and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to propose that the two sides establish a
standing dialogue mechanism at the ministerial or vice-ministerial
level, which will serve as a useful channel for inter-Korean
dialogue. If North Korea (DPRK) agrees, I am ready to dispatch my
envoy to Pyongyang to discuss these matters," said Kim.
</P>
<P>
The president said there were many things that the two sides
could discuss if they were to survive on the peninsula the cold
reality of today's international politics.
</P>
<P>
"The Koreas should open a new chapter of reconciliation,
exchanges and cooperation," said Kim in his national address
titled "Let's begin the second nation-building."
</P>
<P>
The president also said the two governments should initiate a
good relationship for mutual prosperity and coexistence within the
framework of the Basic Agreement on Reconciliation, Non-aggression
and Exchanges and Cooperation between the South and the North.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by both Seoul and Pyongyang in 1992,
but has never been implemented because of continuing
confrontations ever since.
</P>
<P>
In the speech, Kim renewed his stance of not tolerating "armed
provocations" of any kind from the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
A DPRK submarine was caught by the South Korean military on
June 22 after it was found entangled in a fishing net in the South
Korean waters.
</P>
<P>
However, Kim said he would support and encourage the program of
exploiting the tourism resources of the DPRK's Mount Kumgang.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Hyundai Group signed an agreement with the DPRK to
develop Mount Kumgang when its boss Chung Ju-yung visited the
country last June.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, 1,000 South Koreans can tour Mount Kumgang
every day from September this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
