<DOCNO> XIE19980815.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Adopts Unemployment Reduction Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 15 (xinhua) -- The Vietnamese government has
approved a national job creation program in an effort to combat
rising unemployment, the Vietnam News, the English daily, reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's working-age unemployment rate in urban areas soared
to 8.1 percent in Hai Phong, 9.4 percent in Nam Dinh, 9.2 percent
in Thai Binh, 9.3 percent in Guang Ninh and 8.9 percent in Bac
Giang, compared with the average urban unemployment rate under 5.9
percent in 1996 and around 6 percent in 1997, the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate in Vietnam's rural regions is even higher
than 27.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam is expected to have a workforce of over 40 million
people by 2000, compared with 35.9 million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Taking these factors into consideration, Vietnam's national job
creation program set out to create more jobs to ensure employment
for all who have the ability to work. Another goal of the program
is to adopt measures to support the unemployed in their efforts to
find new jobs.
</P>
<P>
The program is designed to create 1.3 to 1.4 million new jobs
to press the urban unemployment rate down to 5 percent, and make
sure that rural labourers have work to do at least 75 percent of
the time.
</P>
<P>
To succeed, economic growth must be realized to generate five
million new jobs. Furthermore, 4.5 million people are to be
trained, according to the program, to increase the skilled
workforce to 25 percent by 2000. 
</P>
