<HEADLINE> Myanmar Accuses Foreign Bodies of Interference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar authorities have
accused four foreign organizations of interfering in the internal
affairs of the country, the official newspaper New Light of
Myanmar reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued by the Ministry of Home
Affairs, the four organizations accused are International
Organization of Democracy in Burma of the United States,
Alternative Asean Network on Burma and Union for Civil Liberty of
Thailand and Initiative International Dialogue of the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
These organizations were strongly condemned for interfering in
the country's internal affairs in the guise of social work and
under the pretext of democracy, and for arranging and financing
the 18 foreigners deported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 18 foreigners, who came to Yangon by air on August 7, were
sentenced by a special court Friday to five years imprisonment on
the account of attempting to incite unrest in the country and were
later released and deported after their punishment was commuted.
</P>
<P>
The foreigners, 10 males and 8 females from the U.S., Thailand,
Malaysia, Indonesia, the Philippines and Australia, were caught
and detained by the authorities last Sunday while reportedly
distributing smuggled leaflets in downtown Yangon in support of
local people's struggle for human rights and democracy. 
</P>
