<HEADLINE> Mahathir: Malaysia May Introduce Drastic Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said Saturday his government may introduce
measures which may appear drastic in its effort to bring about
economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
The proposed measures could raise apprehension among the people
and prompt them to question whether the impending moves would be
helpful, Mahathir said when addressing a meet-the-people rally in
Kota Kinabalu, capital of Sabah state, East Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
He said notwithstanding that the people may have doubts and
suspicion over the proposed measures, they should have faith that
the proposed measures are meant for the nation's and their own
good.
</P>
<P>
"Have faith in the government. Each time we want to adopt an
approach we'll study it in depth first," Mahathir was quoted by
Malaysia's national news agency Bernama as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said all measures undertaken by the government and
designed to bring about economic recovery would be fruitful only
if the people give full support.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia whose economy was badly hit by the regional financial
crisis since last July has already introduced several measures and
approaches, including the establishment of the National Economic
Action Council, to deal with the current economic problems.
Malaysia registered a negative 1.8 percent growth in the first
quarter this year, the first negative growth in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
"But we'll not just end here. Much more have to be done,"
Mahathir said, adding the government's policies or approaches
were never meant to bring hardships to the people.
</P>
<P>
It would only draw up sound plans for the people whose
undivided support was crucial for their successful implementation,
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said speculative raids by currency traders on the ringgit
had not been much of a pressure on the people although the attack
on the currency remained the country's main problem.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said the government's policies and approaches in
dealing with such a situation had considerably sheltered the
people from the heat of the raids by the currency traders.
</P>
<P>
As an aftermath of their actions, the government now had
limited resources to finance development projects and had to defer
many of them, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir also told the rally about a foreign conspiracy out to
destroy the economy and topple the national leadership.
</P>
<P>
He said it was clear that parties behind the conspiracy had
failed in their attempt to change the leadership of the country.
</P>
<P>
"With the people's support, we can still stand tall and
preserve the national sovereignty and dignity," Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir appealed to the people to fully support the government
in its handling of the economic problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
