<HEADLINE> Riot Masterminds in Indonesia Still at Large: Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Police have arrested 16 people
suspected of instigating the May riots in which 1,200 people were
killed, but the masterminds of the mass unrest are yet to be
found, police said.
</P>
<P>
Coordinator of the Commission on Missing Persons and Victims of
Violence Munir said here Friday that those arrested so far are
relatively insignificant figures, the Observer daily reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The detainees are similar to the policemen who were made
scapegoats for May 12 killings at West Jakarta's Trisakti
University, while the real perpetrators remain free, he lamented.
</P>
<P>
"The policy today in solving the case of the riots and the
Trisakti case is just to find scapegoats. There's no strong
resolve to find the real masterminds who should be the first to be
sent to court," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Munir is adamant that the villains are not being touched
because they have strong links to the military and government.
</P>
<P>
Of the 16 people arrested, just three have been investigated by
public prosecutors and will later be sent to court. The others are
still under the custody of the Metro Jaya Police.
</P>
<P>
The masterminds of the May riots succeeded in destroying
thousands of shops and homes, most of them owned by ethnic
Chinese. As many as 170 ethnic Chinese women were raped during the
riots, the National Committee on Human Rights said earlier.
</P>
<P>
Some government officials claim the riots appeared to be a
spontaneous outburst of anger over the price increase fueled by
the economic crisis and Trisakti killings.
</P>
<P>
But witnesses said that in at least 27 areas of Jakarta,
well-organized groups of men, believed to be from the military,
were seen urging mobs to attack buildings, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Authorities are still looking for 20 men suspected to incite
the unrest, said police spokesman Lieutenant Colonel Edward
Aritonang.
</P>
<P>
The 16 already arrested are accused of spearheading the riots
in 10 locations in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
"The arrest of the suspects clarifies the fact that the May
riots were masterminded," said Aritonang.
</P>
<P>
He said police still do not know whether the instigators were
following orders from high-ranking officials.
</P>
<P>
A government panel is now investigating whether elements of the
Armed Forces were involved.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Observer also carried an editorial "Cat and
Mouse", saying that rumors of a new wave of massacres on
Proclamation Day on August 17 have sent shock waves through the
country.
</P>
<P>
The editorial said this shows that the government has not yet
succeeded in providing a sense of security to our brothers of
Chinese origin, who only last May became victims of unsurpassed
looting, ransacking and gang rape, and to whom, say some sources,
law enforcement agencies have deliberately turned a blind eye.
</P>
<P>
"Whether or not current rumors have any semblance of truth,
those who do not want the present government to succeed, have hit
upon an effective kind of cat and mouse game which puts it on the
defensive, always trying to put out the fire after it has burnt
out the whole environs," the editorial said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
