<HEADLINE> Canada Voices Concern Over Instability in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Canada voiced its concern Friday
over the renewed instability in the Congo and the African Great
Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
It also condemned the continuing inter-ethnic conflict in the
African country and the worsening atmosphere of exclusion and
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
"Canada welcomes and supports the efforts of the region's
leaders to ensure the territorial integrity of the Congo and
regrets that their call for a cessation of hostilities made at the
Victoria Falls meeting has fallen on deaf ears," said Foreign
Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy.
</P>
<P>
National reconciliation, at every level and in every region,
must remain the primary objective in the Congo, Axworthy noted.
</P>
<P>
He called on all the parties to the conflict to resume
discussions as soon as possible to implement the constitutional
reforms and to lay the groundwork for democratic public
consultations to legitimize the authorities.
</P>
<P>
"Canada remains deeply concerned by statements that are
exacerbating the violence and ethnic discrimination," Axworthy
added.
</P>
<P>
Canada encouraged all parties in the conflict to ensure that
the human rights of every individual in the Congo were respected, to
cease enlisting children as soldiers, and to show justice and
restraint in order to restore calm, Axworthy said. 
</P>
