<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean President Proposes New Dialogue with DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 15 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim
Dae-jung Saturday proposed that the two sides on the Korean
peninsula form a ministerial-level dialogue forum, saying he would
like to send an envoy to the Democratic People's Republic of Korea
(DPRK) to discuss the proposal.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to mark the 50th anniversary of the founding of the
nation here on Saturday morning, Kim said the proposal is in the
spirit of his hope to remove the "wall of distrust" between the
two sides and to promote bilateral exchanges and cooperation in
accordance with the principles of separating politics and
economics.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to propose that the two sides establish a
standing dialogue mechanism at the ministerial or vice
ministerial-level, which will serve as a useful channel for
inter-Korean dialogue. If North Korea (DPRK) agrees, I am ready to
dispatch my envoy to Pyongyang to discuss these matters," Kim
said. 
