<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Andean Community Nations Guard Against Protectionism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Andean Community is refraining
from taking joint action despite a flood of Asian imports,
Sebastian Alegrett, secretary general of the Andean Community,
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Although some countries like Colombia and Venezuela had adopted
unilateral measures to protect their markets against the massive
imports of Asian products, no joint actions had been agreed within
the community, said Alegrett.
</P>
<P>
He said that last week Venezuela had decided to set prices on
imports at between 100 and 200 percent over their cost.
</P>
<P>
Colombia, in a similar way, approved the application of
safeguards to the import of polyester fibers.
</P>
<P>
Peruvian entrepreneurs in the same sector demanded the
government establish a commission to take measures against
Asian imports.
</P>
<P>
But Alegrett there was no decision about the possibility of
adopting a common policy against the affects of massive
Asian imports because of the risk of protectionism.
</P>
<P>
"It must be examined, pondered, the phenomenon must be
followed, but the governments have not had so far a position of
consensus about this matter," he said.
</P>
<P>
The community was established in 1969 and groups Peru, Bolivia,
Ecuador, Colombia and Venezuela. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
