<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Air force Bombs Foreign Merchant Ship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's air force planes
bombed Friday the foreign merchant ship that had been hijacked by
Rebels of the Liberation Tigers of the Tamil Eelam (LTTE) earlier
to prevent the cargo from falling the hands of LTTE, reports
reaching here said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Two bombers of the air force carried out the bombing operation
while the rebels fired surface to air missiles at the aircraft,
the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Gunmen from the LTTE seized a Dubai-owned merchant vessel with
21 crew members, including 16 Indian nationals.
</P>
<P>
The 6,000-ton ship was on its way to the northern peninsula of
Jaffna from Colombo. The ship was carrying cement and general
cargo for traders in Jaffna city.
</P>
<P>
The ship was hijacked by the rebels Friday morning near
Mullaithivu coast close to a main base of LTTE.
</P>
<P>
Under the support of the air force, Sri Lankan naval vessels
fired the ship and destroyed it, the reports added.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has been fighting against the Sri Lankan government
since 1983 for a separate Tamil state in the north and east of the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
