<HEADLINE> Three Countries Form Free Trade Zone in Lower Danube </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Romania, Moldova and Ukraine
declared Friday the official establishment of the Lower Danube
Euroregion in Galati, Romania.
</P>
<P>
Under a treaty signed in July 1997, the three countries will
step up cross-border trade cooperation in the free trade region,
which includes three cities of Romania, three districts of Moldova
and the State of Odessa of Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the three countries also passed the
constitution of the transnational region and established the Lower
Danube Euroregion Committee, the highest executive body of the
region.
</P>
<P>
Under the constitution, representatives of each country will
take the rotating chairmanship of the committee for two years.
</P>
<P>
Razvan Angheluta, a Romanian, was elected the first chairman of
the committee. 
