<HEADLINE> Indonesian Army Body to Recommend Trial of Prabowo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The Officers Honor Council of
the Indonesian Army would recommend that former commander of the
Army's Special Force (Kopassus) Lt. Gen. Prabowo Subianto be
court-martialled for his alleged involvement in the abductions and
torture of political activists, chief of the council said.
</P>
<P>
"We'll recommend (to Armed Forces Commander Gen. Wirando) that
Prabowo be court-martialled rather than just be given
administrative punishment," Gen. Subagyo Hadissiwoyo said at the
Army's headquarters here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The ultimate decision, however, will be taken by Wiranto
himself, said Subagyo, who is also Army chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
Prabowo, son-in-law of former president Soeharto, and his
successor Maj. Gen. Muchdi Purwopranijono as well as the former
commander of Kopassus Group IV for Intelligence Operations Col.
Chairawan, are currently being investigated by the council for the
abductions of more than 20 political activists early this year.
Ten lower-ranking Kopassus soldiers will be court-martialled for
allegedly carrying out the abductions.
</P>
<P>
Prabowo, who has been questioned twice by the council, admitted
that the abductions took place because he misinterpreted an
instruction from a superior.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers reported that Prabowo may also be involved in
other criminal cases such as riots in May in Jakarta and other big
cities during which about 1,200 people were killed and more than
5,000 shops and buildings damaged or burnt as well as 168 women
were raped by the rioters.
</P>
<P>
The Officers Honor Council was established on August 3 and
started work the next day. It will proceed with its questioning
next Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
