<HEADLINE> Nicaragua Seeks End to Armed Forces Dispute With Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Nicaraguan government is
determined to resolve peacefully a dispute with Costa Rica over
armed forces on their common border, rather than send troops to
the area, Nicaraguan army chief Joaquin Cuadra said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
But Nicaragua was maintaining its ban on Costa Rican
authorities travelling with weapons on the San Juan River, which
separates the two countries, he added.
</P>
<P>
The problem with Costa Rica had to be solved with conversation,
maturity and prudence, said Cuadra.
</P>
<P>
The Nicaraguan government declared on Wednesday that a
two-week-old border agreement with Costa Rica was "invalid and
non-existent" in a dispute over the movement of armed forces along
the boundary line.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, covering a 300-kilometer stretch of the Rio San
Juan River, was signed on July 30.
</P>
<P>
Under current treaties, the waterway is under Nicaraguan
sovereignty, but Costa Rica has the right of free navigation.
</P>
<P>
A conflict arose last month when Nicaragua forbade Costa Rican
armed forces from navigating the river with weapons.
</P>
<P>
Last month's agreement allowed Costa Rican police officers to
keep navigating the river carrying weapons, but only after they
informed Nicaraguan authorities of their plans.
</P>
<P>
This agreement, however, met with strong opposition in
Nicaragua's political circles, resulting in a claim by President
Arnoldo Aleman that it was just a simple "press release." 
</P>
</TEXT>
