<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 15 (Xinhua) -- The Joint Fact-finding Team had
set up three groups to probe the May riots in the Indonesian
capital and other cities, local press Saturday quoted the team's
Chairman Marzuki Darusman as saying.
</P>
<P>
Darusman said that the joint team on Friday set up three groups
respectively in charge of data verification, testimonial affairs
and facts about the victims.
</P>
<P>
"Today (August 14) they have worked and next week we will have
the result of their work," Darusman said.
</P>
<P>
The joint team, which was formed on July 23, involves various
groups such as government officials, military officers,
non-governmental organizations, lawyers and women's organizations.
</P>
<P>
Darusman called on all parties not to make hasty conclusions on
matters related to the May riots as his team needed a conducive
climate to do its best.
</P>
<P>
He also hoped for the people's participation in giving
information so that the team would get a complete picture and make
a recommendation for the government later in October this year.
</P>
<P>
The country saw the worst looting and rioting in decades in
Jakarta and other cities from May 13 to 15. About 1,200 lives were
claimed, and thousands of buildings and vehicles were damaged and
burnt. It was reported that the total number of victims of rape
and sexual harassment from the rioting reached 168.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the government's plan to invite foreign
intelligence agents to Indonesia to take part in the May riots
investigation, Darusman said the joint team must be given the
opportunity to do its best.
</P>
<P>
"We should do what we must do first," he said, adding that he
realized that the government planning to invite foreign
intelligence agents has been influenced by outsiders.
</P>
<P>
Appreciating the government's intention, Darusman said,
"President Habibie may want to show the outside world that we are
serious, but actually we do not need the help of foreigners in the
May riots investigation."
</P>
<P>
Habibie Wednesday ordered Coordinating Minister for Political
and Security Affairs Feisal Tanjung to invite foreign intelligence
agents to Indonesia to examine reports of systematic gang rapes.
</P>
<P>
Members of Indonesian parliament Friday also rejected the
government's plan to invite foreign intelligence agents.
</P>
<P>
They said the government should wait for the Joint Fact-finding
Team to finish its probe into the rapes and use domestic
intelligence agencies, before calling in foreigners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
