<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Asks US to Respect Territorial Integrity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Mexico asked the United
States here Friday to respect its territorial integrity in
operations against drug dealing and the laundering of drugs money.
</P>
<P>
Romero Perez, the Mexican representative at the Hemisphere
Congress for the Prevention of Money Laundering, admitted here the
success of the "Casa Blanca" operation directed by the U.S. Drug
Enforcement Administration (DEA) in Mexican territory, he said
that the U.S. authorities had never consulted with his government.
</P>
<P>
He disagreed with the method of the operations, but he said his
government did not support the illicit activities of the Mexican
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
"For Mexico, as for any other country, it will not be a cause
of pride that the financial institutions in our country were used
for criminals to hide the funds obtained in illegal activities."
</P>
<P>
Twenty-two officials of 12 Mexican banks were detained on the
charges of money laundering in this undercover operation, while
112 others were arrested in Las Vegas and in California, in the
United States, said Perez, who is also an official of the National
Bank and Stocks Commission of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
He also said that three Mexican banks were allegedly involved
in money laundering, 35 million U.S. dollars were frozen, and two
tons of cocaine and four tons of marihuana were seized in the
operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
