<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arena Likely to be U.S. Soccer Team Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Soccer Federation
President Alan Rothenberg plans to hire Bruce Arena as the head
coach of the U.S. men's soccer national team, according to a
press report here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Aren, coach of two-time Major League Soccer champion D.C.
United, is the lone American of the four finalists to replace
Steve Sampson, who resigned after the American team was beaten
0-3 at the World Cup in France. The others are Bora Milutinovic,
Carlos Alberto Parreira and Carlos Queiroz.
</P>
<P>
Arena, 46, has won the wholehearted support from outgoing
Rothenberg, who for weeks had said he preferred to hire a coach
with international experience.
</P>
<P>
Rothenberg interviewed Arena in Orlando on August 2. He
shifted his view after the meeting. He believes Arena can
acquired the experience through the regional events leading to
the 2002 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
"We are still at the point where it needs to make sense for
both parties," Rothenberg said. "We've not discussed details."
</P>
<P>
Arena, whose only international experience came coaching the
1996 U.S. Olympic team, coached D.C. United to the first two MLS
championships. He said yesterday that no offer has been made and
no contract terms have been discussed with USSF officials.
</P>
<P>
"I'm interested," Arena said. "But I think at this point in
time, there would still be a lot of points to be discussed
related to the position. I feel it is an excellent job."
</P>
<P>
Rothenberg has said he would like to announce the new coach
before his term as USSF president expires on August 23. Arena
likely would be offered a two-year contract with two option years
or a one-year deal with multiple options.
</P>
<P>
Former U.S. coach Steve Sampson had a contract for more than
200,000 U.S. dollars this year but operated on a series of
one-year deals. It is believed that Arena likely would complete
his season with the United and take over the new job on Novenmber
1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
