<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hingis Advances to Acura Classic Tennis Semifinals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Top seed Martina Hingis of
Switzerland ousted American Serena Williams in straight sets to
reach the semifinals of the 450,000 U.S. dollars Acura Classic
tennis tournament in Manhattan Beach, California of the United St
ates on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Hingis, who needed a third-set tiebreaker to beat Williams in
the quarterfinals of the Lipton championships in March, rolled
over the U.S. teenager 6-4, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
Hingis will face French Open champion Arantxa Sanchez Vicario
of Spain in Saturday's semifinal after Vicario, the third seed,
overpowered Elena Tatarkova of Ukraine 6-3, 6-3 in another
quarterfinal today.
</P>
<P>
Tonight, second seed Lindsay Davenport of the United States
fights against Natasha Zvereva of Belarus.
</P>
<P>
The winner of the battle will meet defending champion Monica
Seles of the United States in the semifinals. Seles, the fourth
seed, advanced to her third consecutive semifinal Thursday with a
victory over Wimbledon runner-up Nathalie Tauziat of France.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980815.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coetzer, Huber Beaten in Boston Cup Quarterfinals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Top seed Amanda Coetzer of
South Africa and second seed Anke Huber of Germany were beaten
Friday in the quarterfinals of the Boston Cup tennis tournament
in Massachusetts, the United States.
</P>
<P>
Coetzer was upset by seventh seed Barbara Schett of Austria
6-7 (3-7), 6-4, 6-1, while unseeded Mariaan de Swardt of South
Africa ousted Huber 6-3, 7-6 (7-4).
</P>
<P>
The 27-year-old de Swardt will take on third seed American
Lisa Raymond in Saturday's semifinal.
</P>
<P>
Raymond beat fellow American Corina Morariu 7-6 (7-5), 6-2.
Fifth seed Elena Likhovtseva of Russia fights Cara Black of
Zimbabwe, the younger sister of ATP Tour players Wayne and Byron.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980815.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rafter Beats Korda in ATP Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Reigning U.S. Open champion
and fifth seed Patrick Rafter of Australia extended his winning
steak to eight matches after beating Australian Open champion and
third seed Petr Korda of the Czech Republic 6-4, 7-6 (10-8) at
the 2.45 million U.S. dollars ATP Championship in Ohio, the
United States on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Rafter, who claimed his first Super 9 title in last week's du
Maurier Open in Toronto, will face Yevgeny Kafelnikov of Russia
in the semifinals. Kafelnikov moved into the top four when he
disposed of Daniel Vacek of the Czech Republic, his doubles
partner 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Unseeded Mgnus Larsson entered his first ATP Tour semifinal on
American soil in three years by beating fellow Swede Thomas
Johansson 6-4, 7-6 (7-2).
</P>
<P>
Top seed and defending champion Pete Sampras of the United
States, looking to reclaim his world number one ranking, plays
fellow American Vince Spadea tonight in the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
Sampras can recapture the No. 1 ranking from Marcelo Rios of
Chile if he wins this event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980815.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wyatt Creech Appointed New Zealand Deputy PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 15 (Xinhua) -- Wyatt Creech, deputy leader
of the National Party, the major ruling party in New Zealand, has
been appointed deputy prime minister to replace Winston Peters
who was sacked Friday.
</P>
<P>
Creech was minister of education and leader of the House before
the promotion.
</P>
<P>
The announcement of promoting Creech to the deputy prime
minister was made Friday by Prime Minister Jenny Shipley, The
Dominion, a Wellington-based newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Bill Birch was appointed treasurer. Birch also continues as
minister of finance.
</P>
<P>
Winston Peters is the leader of the NZ First, the minority
partner of the National Party in the current coalition government.
Shipley accused Peters of violating principles of cabinet
collective responsibility and publicly criticizing government
policy regarding the sale of the government's shareholding in
Wellington Airport, and dismissed him from the post of deputy
prime minister and treasurer. While announcing the dismissal of
Peters, Shipley said she had asked that the Coalition Disputes
Committee be called together in order to have the principles of
collective responsibility confirmed as a clearly understood
requirement of the coalition.
</P>
<P>
The Dominion quoted the prime minister as saying that she
intended to "establish a National-led minority government in the
future", if the coalition disputes procedure could not bring a
satisfactory solution.
</P>
<P>
The dismissal of Peters was followed by an announcement of
selling the government's 66 percent shareholding in Wellington
Airport to Infratil New Zealand for 96.36 million NZ dollars
(about 49 million U.S. dollars). Infratil NZ is jointly owned by
New Zealand Airports, a consortium led by Infratil; British
investment groups Alliance Life Common Fund; and Foreign and
Colonial Special Utilities Investment Trust.  
</P>
</TEXT>
