<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Evidence of Manipulation in Natural Gas Futures: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The International Petroleum
Exchange (IPE) said on Friday that it finds no evidence of price
manipulation on its natural gas futures contract after
investigation.
</P>
<P>
Over the last week gas prices have risen generally, in the
futures and underlying physical markets. UK prompt natural gas
prices have risen in recent days, reaching almost 13 pence,
unusual in Summer months when demand is at its lowest in the year.
</P>
<P>
An industry association representing the UK's largest energy
buyers has suggested that there are rumors that the market has
been manipulated higher in order to influence long term contract
negotiations that are currently underway.
</P>
<P>
However, after having examined closely events on the futures
market and the pattern of trades, the parties carrying out the
trades and the underlying clients, the IPE's Compliance department
concluded that there is no evidence of manipulation.
</P>
<P>
"In this case we have received no official complaint, no hard
evidence of any wrongdoing, merely unsubstantiated rumors. We have
nonetheless investigated these rumors and can find no evidence of
manipulation." said John Mackeonis, Executive Vice President for
Market Supervision at the IPE, in a statement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
