<HEADLINE> Russian, U.S. Presidents Talk on Forthcoming Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
and U.S. President Bill Clinton Friday had a 40-minute telephone
conversation on their forthcoming summit, according to the
Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
The Russian presidential press service in a statement said that
the two leaders "discussed practical preparation for the upcoming
Russian-American summit to be held in Moscow in early September
this year."
</P>
<P>
The summit will become a milestone in Russian-American
interaction, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The conversation also focused on some salient international
problems, including the situation in Kosovo and Iraq, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was interested in the financial situation in Russia,
following the turmoil on the world money market, and in the
anti-crisis measures being carried out by the Russian government.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the U.S. president energetically supported
the Russian leadership's efforts toward overcoming its problems.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ways of ratifying the START-2 treaty by the Russian
State Duma, the lower house of parliament, were also discussed
during the two presidents' telephone conversation. 
</P>
