<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hard Water Linking to Children Eczema </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- Hard water is a major risk factor
for eczema in primary school children, British researchers said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Water hardness was more strongly linked with the painful, itchy
skin disorder than traffic pollution or any other suggested
hazard, rfesearchers from the the University of Nottingham
reported in The Lancet medical journal.
</P>
<P>
Researchers found that 17.3 percent of primary school children
living in areas with hard water had suffered eczema for a year,
and 25.4 percent had the disorder all their lives.
</P>
<P>
For soft-water areas the figures were 12 percent and 21.2
percent respectively, the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
The study involved 4,141 primary school children and 3,499
secondary school children in southern Nottinghamshire in the UK.
</P>
<P>
The scientists said water hardness may worsen or prolong
existing eczema because calcium and magnesium in the water act as
chemical irritants.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
