<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Launches Tab Bid to End Beef Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- A system for keeping tabs on all
cattle from birth to death is being introduced in Britain in a bid
to persuade the European Union to lift its ban on British beef
exports.
</P>
<P>
British farmers hope the new 35 million pounds (about 56
million U.S. dollars) cattle tracking service, which comes into
operation next month, will help them prove their herds are free of
the "mad cow disease", according to local media reports.
</P>
<P>
Final trials of the system, whereby every animal in the country
will be tagged, are taking place in Cumbria.
</P>
<P>
Each animal must, by law, be registered within a week of its
birth, with its history to be documented throughout its life on a
form similar to a vehicle registration document, according to the
new system.
</P>
<P>
And every time an animal is bought or sold, the tracking
service will have to be notified. Farmers who fail to register
their cattle will be fined or even sent to prison.
</P>
<P>
British Agriculture Minister Jeff Rooker was quoted as saying:
"We hope for an early lifting of the ban." He told BBC Radio that
he hoped the ban would be lifted by the end of the year and that
negotiations were taking place "on a daily basis".
</P>
<P>
He added that the new system was in addition to existing
efforts and that "there is no excuse for the beef ban not being
lifted now".
</P>
<P>
Those running the scheme for the Ministry of Agriculture
believe it could be a critical factor in persuading European vets
and politicians to lift the ban on British beef.
</P>
<P>
The EU ban has been in place since March 1996 when the UK
Government admitted there was a possible link between Bovine
Spongiform Encephalopathy (BSE) - or 'mad cow disease' - and
Creutzfeld Jakob's Disease, a fatal condition affecting humans.
</P>
<P>
One month later it was announced that all animals aged over 30
months at the time of slaughter would be destroyed rather than be
allowed to enter the human food chain.
</P>
<P>
Since 1996, more than a million unwanted calves have been
slaughtered, and more than two and a quarter million older cattle
killed. The total cost of BSE to British taxpayers is set to top
4 billion pounds or over 6.4 billion U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
