<HEADLINE> U.N. Budget for 2000-2001 to Reduce to $2.46 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The preliminary estimates
of the United Nations budget for 2000-2001 amount to 2.4685
billion U.S. dollars, 63.8 million dollars or 2.5 percent less
than the current budget period 1998-1999.
</P>
<P>
The figures were disclosed here Friday by a General Assembly
document containing Secretary-General Kofi Annan's report on the
subject to be deliberated in next general assembly beginning
September 9.
</P>
<P>
Annan proposed that the budget for the next biennium reflects
the current priorities given to maintenance of peace and security
and promotion of sustained economic development of developing
countries, including Africa.
</P>
<P>
Despite the overall reduction of the budget, allocations for
the item "international cooperation for development" is expected
to rise from the current 272.6 million dollars to 276.5 million
dollars for the next biennium.
</P>
<P>
The new budget estimates are seen in line with the spirits of
Annan's reform plan for an efficient U.N. to meet the challenges
of the next century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
