<HEADLINE> MIGA Increases Guarantee Coverage for Fiscal Year 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- The Multilateral Investment
Guarantee Agency (MIGA) Friday announced that it issued 830.9
million U.S. dollars in new coverage for projects in 26 developing
member countries in fiscal year 1998 ended on June 30.
</P>
<P>
This represents a moderate increase as compared with 714
million dollars in 25 developing countries in fiscal year 1997. In
FY 1998, MIGA broadened its portfolio by writing coverage for
investments in 10 new countries-- Angola, Bolivia, Cape Verde,
Dominican Republic, Equatorial Guinea, India, Kenya, Mozambique,
Ukraine and Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
MIGA, formed in 1988, is a member of the World Bank Group. It's
main mandate is to encourage foreign direct investment into
developing countries by providing political risk insurance against
such risks as transfer restriction, expropriation, breach of
contract as well as war and civil disturbance.
</P>
<P>
The development impacts of MIGA's FY 1998 projects includes
about 8,000 jobs created and approximately 6.1 billion in foreign
direct investments facilitated in the developing countries in
which they were located.
</P>
<P>
In past 10 years, MIGA have issued 348 guarantee contracts
which have facilitated an estimated 25 billion dollars in foreign
direct investment in 62 developing and transition member
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
