<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Yeltsin to Take Quick Action on Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Friday urged Russian President Boris Yeltsin to take quick,
decisive action to restore stability and confidence in Russia's
economy.
</P>
<P>
During a 40-minute phone call, Clinton received assurances from
Boris Yeltsin on Friday that Russia is taking the necessary steps
to weather its latest economic crisis, White House spokesman Mike
McCurry told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The leaders did not discuss whether a new aid package from the
West would be needed, he said.
</P>
<P>
"This was not a phone call about money. It was a phone call
about doing the things necessary" to stabilize an economy that has
been struggling, McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
"President Yeltsin sounded strong and confident in his economic
team," McCurry said. "They discussed some of the steps that will
be necessary to, over the long term, assure economic stability in
Russia."
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, a U.S. official told reporters that Clinton
encouraged Yeltsin to take some decisive steps in the next few
days that would help change the market psychology, so to speak, in
restoring confidence.
</P>
<P>
"The president encouraged President Yeltsin to work with his
economic team and take some action sooner rather than later," said
the U.S. official.
</P>
<P>
"They need to keep doing the things that they need to do under
the IMF program. That will both send the right signal to the
markets and improve the climate when the IMF evaluates release of
the next tranche," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and Yeltsin will meet in Moscow early in September with
economic issues likely to dominate the summit.  
</P>
